WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:04.255
Prof: Okay,
today we're going to talk a

00:00:04.255 --> 00:00:06.190
little bit more about Social
Security.

00:00:06.190 --> 00:00:09.052
Social Security,
remember, is the biggest

00:00:09.052 --> 00:00:11.200
program the government runs.
 

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:14.146
Its annual expenditures are
slightly bigger than the

00:00:14.146 --> 00:00:17.440
military expenditures every
year, and those two things are

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:19.520
way bigger than everything else.
 

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:23.417
It's been the biggest program
the government's run since the

00:00:23.417 --> 00:00:26.411
New Deal,
since Franklin Delano Roosevelt

00:00:26.411 --> 00:00:29.180
put it into effect in the late
1930s,

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:31.910
and it seems to be broke.
 

00:00:31.910 --> 00:00:35.576
So it lasted for 70 years,
and now it seems on the verge

00:00:35.576 --> 00:00:36.710
of going broke.
 

00:00:36.710 --> 00:00:39.590
So what happened and how can we
fix it?

00:00:39.590 --> 00:00:41.888
And as I said,
this has been a topic of

00:00:41.888 --> 00:00:44.248
conversation,
presidential conversation,

00:00:44.248 --> 00:00:45.700
at least since 2000.
 

00:00:45.700 --> 00:00:47.370
There were a bunch of
commissions before that,

00:00:47.370 --> 00:00:51.800
looking at the problem,
and what I said last time was,

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:55.090
the general public and our
politicians seem completely

00:00:55.090 --> 00:00:57.140
confused about what's going on.
 

00:00:57.140 --> 00:01:00.003
So we need to figure out,
how could it be that the

00:01:00.003 --> 00:01:01.228
program went broke?
 

00:01:01.228 --> 00:01:05.120
Should that have been a
surprise, and how can we fix it?

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:08.191
And the three standard things
everybody says is,

00:01:08.191 --> 00:01:11.198
President Bush and many people
like him saying,

00:01:11.198 --> 00:01:13.879
"Well, the system's going
broke.

00:01:13.879 --> 00:01:17.144
The rate of return young people
like you are going to get is

00:01:17.144 --> 00:01:18.750
less than 2 percent a year.
 

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:19.860
That's terrible.
 

00:01:19.860 --> 00:01:22.584
Any bond, any stock,
you can expect a much higher

00:01:22.584 --> 00:01:25.310
return than that,
so the program's just awful.

00:01:25.310 --> 00:01:29.080
We should stop it or privatize
it."

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:30.920
I'll explain what privatizing
means.

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:33.340
In that way,
your money, instead of going to

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:35.616
old people,
will be put in the stock market

00:01:35.616 --> 00:01:38.300
and you'll get a higher rate of
return and you'll do much

00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:38.780
better.
 

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:42.287
Then a second thing people say
is, "Well,

00:01:42.287 --> 00:01:44.860
the thing lasted all this time.
 

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:47.019
I mean, what's really gone
different?

00:01:47.019 --> 00:01:49.290
What could possibly have caused
the change?

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:54.680
It must be those dastardly baby
boom generation-ers,

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:58.453
like me, who are headed towards
retirement in another 20 or 30

00:01:58.453 --> 00:02:00.099
years,
and they're going to bankrupt

00:02:00.099 --> 00:02:00.549
the system.
 

00:02:00.549 --> 00:02:03.013
There are going to be so many
of those old geezers hanging

00:02:03.013 --> 00:02:05.488
around needing to get paid,
that young people like you

00:02:05.488 --> 00:02:07.120
won't be able to carry the
burden,

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:08.628
and so it's our fault."
 

00:02:08.628 --> 00:02:11.538
And then there are the people,
the naysayers,

00:02:11.538 --> 00:02:14.628
Gore chief among them,
but many others,

00:02:14.628 --> 00:02:19.060
Obama now similarly saying,
slightly similar things,

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:21.182
saying, "Well,
privatization doesn't make any

00:02:21.182 --> 00:02:21.530
sense.
 

00:02:21.530 --> 00:02:24.854
It's logically impossible,
because if you take the taxes

00:02:24.854 --> 00:02:27.030
that the young people are
paying,

00:02:27.030 --> 00:02:29.590
and tell them,
those Social Security taxes,

00:02:29.590 --> 00:02:31.408
they can invest in private
accounts,

00:02:31.408 --> 00:02:34.050
the stock market,
with their own name on it,

00:02:34.050 --> 00:02:37.008
then how are we going to give
money to the old people now?

00:02:37.008 --> 00:02:38.819
So you'll just be screwing the
old generation."

00:02:38.819 --> 00:02:40.788
So privatization is impossible.
 

00:02:40.788 --> 00:02:43.479
So those are the three most
standard things people say.

00:02:43.479 --> 00:02:45.690
All three of them have some
truth to them,

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:48.930
but on the whole,
they're substantially wrong,

00:02:48.930 --> 00:02:52.324
completely wrong,
and once we clarify what stage

00:02:52.324 --> 00:02:54.925
the system is in,
we'll be able to think about

00:02:54.925 --> 00:02:56.080
what the right solution is.
 

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:58.895
I'm going to tell you my
solution which,

00:02:58.895 --> 00:03:03.157
as I said, is not universally
admired, but I'll see what you

00:03:03.157 --> 00:03:04.530
think about it.
 

00:03:04.530 --> 00:03:10.149
So the program came into effect
in what was the greatest or the

00:03:10.149 --> 00:03:14.408
biggest of the New Deal advances
made by FDR.

00:03:14.408 --> 00:03:19.574
And I just thought I'd play you
this tape of him signing it into

00:03:19.574 --> 00:03:22.141
law,
and behind him is the Secretary

00:03:22.141 --> 00:03:23.870
of Labor,
Frances Perkins,

00:03:23.870 --> 00:03:26.996
who you'll see in a second,
played a huge role in this,

00:03:26.996 --> 00:03:29.169
since she was the first woman
in the Cabinet.

00:03:29.169 --> 00:03:31.727
And by the way,
in my generation,

00:03:31.727 --> 00:03:36.202
there are many women named
Frances, because their parents

00:03:36.202 --> 00:03:38.199
named them after her.
 

00:03:38.199 --> 00:03:43.120
So here's the--let's see if
this works.

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:54.288
&gt;
 

00:03:54.288 --> 00:03:58.163
Franklin D. Roosevelt:
Today a hope of many years'

00:03:58.163 --> 00:04:00.930
standing is in large part
fulfilled.

00:04:00.930 --> 00:04:04.951
The civilization of the past
hundred years,

00:04:04.951 --> 00:04:10.411
with its startling industrial
changes, has tended more and

00:04:10.411 --> 00:04:13.378
more to make life insecure.
 

00:04:13.378 --> 00:04:17.706
Young people have come to
wonder what would be their lot

00:04:17.706 --> 00:04:19.910
when they came to old age.
 

00:04:19.910 --> 00:04:25.860
The man with a job has wondered
how long the job would last.

00:04:25.860 --> 00:04:31.649
This Social Security measure
gives at least some protection

00:04:31.649 --> 00:04:37.038
to thirty millions of our
citizens who will reap direct

00:04:37.038 --> 00:04:41.829
benefits through unemployment
compensation,

00:04:41.829 --> 00:04:46.764
through old-age pensions and
through increased services for

00:04:46.764 --> 00:04:52.040
the protection of children and
the prevention of ill health.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:56.382
We can never insure one hundred
percent of the population

00:04:56.382 --> 00:05:01.113
against one hundred percent of
the hazards and vicissitudes of

00:05:01.113 --> 00:05:04.401
life,
but we have tried to frame a

00:05:04.401 --> 00:05:09.785
law which will give some measure
of protection to the average

00:05:09.785 --> 00:05:14.629
citizen and to his family
against the loss of a job and

00:05:14.629 --> 00:05:17.860
against poverty-ridden old age.
 

00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:21.939
It seems to me that if the
Senate and the House of

00:05:21.939 --> 00:05:26.685
Representatives in this long and
arduous session have done

00:05:26.685 --> 00:05:30.600
nothing more than pass this
security bill,

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:35.137
Social Security Act,
the session would be regarded

00:05:35.137 --> 00:05:37.639
as historic for all time.
 

00:05:37.639 --> 00:05:39.620
&gt;
 

00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:41.550
Prof: Okay,
well, it was regarded as

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:45.511
historic for all time,
and let me now explain what

00:05:45.511 --> 00:05:49.399
Social Security does,
and what the rules are.

00:05:49.399 --> 00:06:06.889
And I have to open another file.
 

00:06:06.889 --> 00:06:10.675
I forgot where I put--I hope
it's--I wonder whether

00:06:10.675 --> 00:06:14.160
it's--sorry, I opened the wrong
year, I see.

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:21.560
I'm living in the past.
 

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:23.560
Sorry, that was last year's.
 

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:47.750
 
 

00:06:47.750 --> 00:06:55.310
Okay, so we went through all
this last time.

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:59.709
So, after passing legislation,
a massive publicity campaign

00:06:59.709 --> 00:07:03.045
was launched,
convincing people that this was

00:07:03.045 --> 00:07:04.259
a good idea.
 

00:07:04.259 --> 00:07:06.283
And not everybody thought it
was such a good idea,

00:07:06.283 --> 00:07:06.819
by the way.
 

00:07:06.819 --> 00:07:09.689
And so, you know,
this is an example of the

00:07:09.689 --> 00:07:12.970
advertisements that were
plastered everybody,

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:15.259
you know, telling you about how
much you were going to get,

00:07:15.259 --> 00:07:17.379
money after you retired.
 

00:07:17.379 --> 00:07:20.589
Now what was the idea of Social
Security?

00:07:20.589 --> 00:07:23.444
The idea was that lots of
people, when they were young,

00:07:23.444 --> 00:07:26.192
didn't really have the
foresight to imagine what life

00:07:26.192 --> 00:07:28.519
was going to be like when they
were old.

00:07:28.519 --> 00:07:32.485
In fact, in the late 1930s,
the most destitute of Americans

00:07:32.485 --> 00:07:35.483
were the old,
and so the idea was to force

00:07:35.483 --> 00:07:37.930
them to save when they were
young,

00:07:37.930 --> 00:07:41.148
and then the money would be
there--would be invested in US

00:07:41.148 --> 00:07:43.519
Treasury bonds and accumulate
interest,

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:46.000
and the money would be there
when they got old.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:49.279
So it was imagined to be a
prefunded system,

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:52.661
prefunded meaning the money
comes in and it's that money

00:07:52.661 --> 00:07:56.041
which is going to then pay
people later when they get to

00:07:56.041 --> 00:07:56.779
old age.
 

00:07:56.779 --> 00:07:58.954
And the idea was,
you were going to collect

00:07:58.954 --> 00:08:01.389
enough taxes so that when you
got to be old,

00:08:01.389 --> 00:08:04.300
you would get 40 percent--every
year,

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:06.769
you would be receiving,
the average person,

00:08:06.769 --> 00:08:09.786
recipient, retiree,
would be receiving 40 percent

00:08:09.786 --> 00:08:12.930
of the average wage of the
average young worker.

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:14.672
And, you know,
the idea is that when you're

00:08:14.672 --> 00:08:16.000
older, you have less expenses.
 

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.007
You probably already own your
house, your children are out of

00:08:20.007 --> 00:08:24.149
the house, so 40 percent should
be enough to keep you going.

00:08:24.149 --> 00:08:26.947
It was certainly more than the
average old person had at the

00:08:26.947 --> 00:08:27.278
time.
 

00:08:27.278 --> 00:08:31.233
Now this you would get for your
entire life, so when Roosevelt

00:08:31.233 --> 00:08:34.344
called it insurance,
what was the main thing that

00:08:34.344 --> 00:08:35.769
you were insuring?
 

00:08:35.769 --> 00:08:39.879
Well, there's a side part of
the program which he mentioned,

00:08:39.879 --> 00:08:42.667
which is insuring people of
disabilities,

00:08:42.667 --> 00:08:44.129
things like that.
 

00:08:44.129 --> 00:08:49.578
But that's a 1--out of the 12.4
percent tax, it's something like

00:08:49.578 --> 00:08:50.788
1.8 percent.
 

00:08:50.788 --> 00:08:55.143
But the main part of the
program is insurance against

00:08:55.143 --> 00:08:55.730
what?
 

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:56.490
Yes?
 

00:08:56.490 --> 00:08:57.210
Student: Living too long.
 

00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:58.178
Prof: Living too long.
 

00:08:58.178 --> 00:09:01.158
So you get the money your
entire life, no matter how long

00:09:01.158 --> 00:09:04.350
you live, so you're being
insured against living too long.

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:05.500
Exactly.
 

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:09.179
So what happened was,
of course in the first year,

00:09:09.179 --> 00:09:12.558
a lot of people were starting
to pay taxes.

00:09:12.558 --> 00:09:15.350
And in the second year,
they were paying more taxes,

00:09:15.350 --> 00:09:17.066
and of course,
they were still not retired

00:09:17.066 --> 00:09:18.663
yet,
so they weren't actually giving

00:09:18.663 --> 00:09:21.977
out the money to anybody,
and this fund was starting to

00:09:21.977 --> 00:09:22.879
accumulate.
 

00:09:22.879 --> 00:09:25.653
So Frances Perkins said,
"Well, what are we doing

00:09:25.653 --> 00:09:26.019
here?
 

00:09:26.019 --> 00:09:28.504
The whole point is that we've
got all these old people,

00:09:28.504 --> 00:09:29.009
you know.
 

00:09:29.009 --> 00:09:30.058
It's just the Depression.
 

00:09:30.058 --> 00:09:32.268
We haven't come out of the
Depression yet."--World War

00:09:32.268 --> 00:09:33.029
II hasn't started.
 

00:09:33.029 --> 00:09:35.335
It won't, for the US,
start for a few more years,

00:09:35.335 --> 00:09:35.960
by the way.
 

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:39.120
"So there are all these
old people sitting here,

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.918
totally destitute,
and we've got all this money

00:09:41.918 --> 00:09:43.558
also just sitting here.
 

00:09:43.558 --> 00:09:45.610
It really doesn't make
sense,"

00:09:45.610 --> 00:09:46.470
she said.
 

00:09:46.470 --> 00:09:49.633
"What we ought to do is
take the money the young people

00:09:49.633 --> 00:09:52.743
are paying in and give it to the
old people who are already

00:09:52.743 --> 00:09:53.279
there.
 

00:09:53.279 --> 00:09:56.407
That way we are going to be
saving these old people and the

00:09:56.407 --> 00:09:58.285
young people,
when they get old,

00:09:58.285 --> 00:10:01.423
they'll be saved themselves,
because there'll be more young

00:10:01.423 --> 00:10:04.072
people coming along afterwards
who can pay taxes in when

00:10:04.072 --> 00:10:05.893
they're young,
and today's young,

00:10:05.893 --> 00:10:08.190
when they're old,
will then collect those taxes.

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:12.125
They'll be reimbursed for what
they contributed when they were

00:10:12.125 --> 00:10:13.028
young."
 

00:10:13.028 --> 00:10:17.889
Well, so Roosevelt resisted for
a while.

00:10:17.889 --> 00:10:21.320
Frances Perkins was apparently,
incredibly persuasive person.

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:25.596
One person at the time named
Witt, who was on the Social

00:10:25.596 --> 00:10:29.173
Security commission,
tried to tell her that was

00:10:29.173 --> 00:10:32.048
going to lead to budget
problems.

00:10:32.048 --> 00:10:36.458
She said that he was a
half-Witt, and that we had a

00:10:36.458 --> 00:10:38.399
more urgent problem.
 

00:10:38.399 --> 00:10:40.822
Not that she doubted him,
but the problem was more

00:10:40.822 --> 00:10:43.642
urgent, and so that was the only
way to solve the problem,

00:10:43.642 --> 00:10:44.779
the current crisis.
 

00:10:44.779 --> 00:10:48.383
So they finally agreed to move
the system from a prefunded

00:10:48.383 --> 00:10:50.658
system, to a pay as you go
system.

00:10:50.658 --> 00:10:53.692
So the money coming in from
current workers is used to pay

00:10:53.692 --> 00:10:55.288
directly to the old workers.
 

00:10:55.288 --> 00:10:59.581
So I don't want to get into all
these little variations that got

00:10:59.581 --> 00:11:00.058
made.
 

00:11:00.058 --> 00:11:04.336
So the program's called the Old
Age Survivors and Disability

00:11:04.336 --> 00:11:05.570
Insurance Plan.
 

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:08.308
The insurance is mainly for
living too long,

00:11:08.308 --> 00:11:11.563
but also in case you get
disabled, or in case you have

00:11:11.563 --> 00:11:15.620
children and you're disabled,
you die, they get something.

00:11:15.620 --> 00:11:18.618
Okay, so it's a combination of
insurance, disability,

00:11:18.618 --> 00:11:21.558
but the main insurance is for
living a long time.

00:11:21.558 --> 00:11:25.908
So as I said,
the tax now is 12.4 percent,

00:11:25.908 --> 00:11:29.408
up to a cap of 106,800 dollars.
 

00:11:29.408 --> 00:11:32.596
So if you make more than
106,800 dollars,

00:11:32.596 --> 00:11:35.624
you pay, you know,
13,000 or something,

00:11:35.624 --> 00:11:39.210
and then nothing more on Social
Security.

00:11:39.210 --> 00:11:42.908
Okay, so the Social Security
tax stops at 106,800.

00:11:42.908 --> 00:11:46.509
So the income tax,
I'm losing track of what it is,

00:11:46.509 --> 00:11:48.860
and whether we're going to go
back to the old one,

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:51.500
but let's say it was 38
percent, 39 percent,

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:54.399
something like that,
if you had to pay that income

00:11:54.399 --> 00:11:58.190
tax and on top of it pay Social
Security tax of 12.4 percent,

00:11:58.190 --> 00:12:00.259
you'd be over 50 percent taxed.
 

00:12:00.259 --> 00:12:04.028
So needless to say,
some of the people who think we

00:12:04.028 --> 00:12:08.477
can solve our Social Security
problem by eliminating the cap

00:12:08.477 --> 00:12:12.774
would be imposing a gigantic
marginal tax rate on a lot of

00:12:12.774 --> 00:12:16.470
people who don't have a marginal
tax rate--

00:12:16.470 --> 00:12:18.308
who have already high marginal
tax rate.

00:12:18.308 --> 00:12:21.490
That would make it sky high,
so that's been resisted.

00:12:21.490 --> 00:12:24.570
So 94 percent of workers are
below the cap anyway,

00:12:24.570 --> 00:12:26.450
so we're talking about the top
6 percent,

00:12:26.450 --> 00:12:29.668
most of which--you'll be in
that top 6 percent,

00:12:29.668 --> 00:12:34.690
so you won't have to pay on the
margin Social Security tax.

00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:36.960
So there's the taxes,
12.4 percent,

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:39.230
and then there are the
benefits.

00:12:39.230 --> 00:12:40.759
Now how do the benefits work?
 

00:12:40.759 --> 00:12:41.870
How are they determined?
 

00:12:41.870 --> 00:12:46.230
So the tax, as I said,
you just take your income below

00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:49.440
106,000 and you pay 12.4 percent
tax.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:51.610
So how do the benefits work?
 

00:12:51.610 --> 00:12:55.303
This is a little bit
complicated, but it's actually a

00:12:55.303 --> 00:12:57.009
very interesting plan.
 

00:12:57.009 --> 00:13:00.850
What they do is they look at
your entire lifetime earnings.

00:13:00.850 --> 00:13:03.100
You're not going to get
benefits till after you retire,

00:13:03.100 --> 00:13:05.658
so you've got your whole life
history behind you,

00:13:05.658 --> 00:13:08.570
and they say,
"Let's look at,

00:13:08.570 --> 00:13:13.001
every year, what the fraction
of your wage was relative to the

00:13:13.001 --> 00:13:15.110
economy wide average."
 

00:13:15.110 --> 00:13:16.639
So it's your relative earning.
 

00:13:16.639 --> 00:13:20.912
So when you're young,
it's probably going to be .8,

00:13:20.912 --> 00:13:21.340
.9.
 

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:24.184
If you go to Yale,
it's probably going to be

00:13:24.184 --> 00:13:26.302
1.5,2, you know,
soon thereafter,

00:13:26.302 --> 00:13:27.230
all right?
 

00:13:27.230 --> 00:13:29.789
Okay, and it might get even
higher, but anyway,

00:13:29.789 --> 00:13:32.740
so that's the relative earning
you have every year.

00:13:32.740 --> 00:13:35.804
So then they say,
"Let's average your 35

00:13:35.804 --> 00:13:40.124
best relative earning years and
just take the sum and divide by

00:13:40.124 --> 00:13:41.029
35."
 

00:13:41.029 --> 00:13:44.491
So what is your average
lifetime relative wage,

00:13:44.491 --> 00:13:45.320
you know?
 

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:47.139
For the average person,
it's going to be 1.

00:13:47.139 --> 00:13:48.984
For some people,
it might be .8,

00:13:48.984 --> 00:13:51.423
for some people,
it might be 2 or 3 or 10,

00:13:51.423 --> 00:13:51.960
okay.
 

00:13:51.960 --> 00:13:54.770
Now the first--all right,
so you've got your average

00:13:54.770 --> 00:13:56.149
relative lifetime wage.
 

00:13:56.149 --> 00:13:57.798
What do you make when you
retire?

00:13:57.798 --> 00:14:01.496
Well, when you hit an age,
which, you know,

00:14:01.496 --> 00:14:05.283
they're adjusting now,
but it used to be 65,

00:14:05.283 --> 00:14:08.804
when you hit 65,
they compute the average

00:14:08.804 --> 00:14:10.389
wage--sorry.
 

00:14:10.389 --> 00:14:13.509
When you hit 65,
you're going to be paid a

00:14:13.509 --> 00:14:18.149
fraction of the average wage in
the economy when you're 65.

00:14:18.149 --> 00:14:21.590
So what is the fraction that
you're paid?

00:14:21.590 --> 00:14:25.428
Well, that depends on what your
historical average wage was.

00:14:25.428 --> 00:14:28.350
So let's just see what the
function is.

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:33.092
So, if your average wage was 1,
equal to the average wage of

00:14:33.092 --> 00:14:35.124
the economy,
your entire,

00:14:35.124 --> 00:14:38.490
over those 35 years,
so you're the average guy,

00:14:38.490 --> 00:14:41.220
then you get,
you see, that's near .4.

00:14:41.220 --> 00:14:46.192
It's actually .44,
so you get 44 percent of the

00:14:46.192 --> 00:14:50.950
average wage at the time you
retire, okay?

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:56.720
If on the other hand,
you made 10 percent of the--

00:14:56.720 --> 00:14:59.618
your relative wage historically
was 10 percent of the average

00:14:59.618 --> 00:15:02.846
wage in the economy,
you would get 9 percent of the

00:15:02.846 --> 00:15:05.460
average wage at the time you
retire.

00:15:05.460 --> 00:15:07.850
So you can see that this is
what's called a concave

00:15:07.850 --> 00:15:10.625
function, just like our utility
function, those diminishing

00:15:10.625 --> 00:15:11.629
marginal returns.
 

00:15:11.629 --> 00:15:15.397
So it means that if you're
earning very little through your

00:15:15.397 --> 00:15:18.450
life, you're going to get a much
better deal.

00:15:18.450 --> 00:15:21.740
You're going to be paid--the
ratio of relative wage

00:15:21.740 --> 00:15:25.888
historically to what you get of
the young people's wage is going

00:15:25.888 --> 00:15:28.899
to be .9,
then the slope drops to .32,

00:15:28.899 --> 00:15:32.408
then it drops to .15 and after
you're double--

00:15:32.408 --> 00:15:35.832
it's actually,
I think, 1.99--after you're

00:15:35.832 --> 00:15:39.979
double the average--
if your historical average wage

00:15:39.979 --> 00:15:44.450
was more than twice the average
wage in the whole economy,

00:15:44.450 --> 00:15:45.840
it doesn't do you any good.
 

00:15:45.840 --> 00:15:47.100
Might as well have been twice.
 

00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:50.619
If it's 4 times,
10 times, you don't get any

00:15:50.619 --> 00:15:51.519
increase.
 

00:15:51.519 --> 00:15:55.375
Okay, so you can see why it
makes some sense to have a cap

00:15:55.375 --> 00:15:58.801
to the taxation,
because people who are making

00:15:58.801 --> 00:16:02.480
10 times the average wage,
you know, let's say they're

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:04.629
making a million dollars
nowadays,

00:16:04.629 --> 00:16:08.101
they aren't going to see any
benefit from having contributed

00:16:08.101 --> 00:16:09.808
so much to Social Security.
 

00:16:09.808 --> 00:16:15.905
Their benefits would be just
the same as if they only made

00:16:15.905 --> 00:16:18.580
200,000 dollars a year.
 

00:16:18.580 --> 00:16:21.065
Okay, so anyway,
you see that there's a

00:16:21.065 --> 00:16:24.990
connection between how much you
made when you were young,

00:16:24.990 --> 00:16:26.980
how much you get paid when
you're old,

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:29.049
but the connection is a concave
thing.

00:16:29.049 --> 00:16:31.168
So it redistributes income.
 

00:16:31.168 --> 00:16:34.873
People who had very low average
wages when they were working get

00:16:34.873 --> 00:16:37.988
a better deal from Social
Security than people who had

00:16:37.988 --> 00:16:40.808
high relative wages while they
were working.

00:16:40.808 --> 00:16:43.730
And that's a cornerstone of the
idea.

00:16:43.730 --> 00:16:49.480
It's meant to help protect the
people who are very poor.

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:52.700
And so it doesn't pay everybody
equally.

00:16:52.700 --> 00:16:57.038
Still, you get some return from
having contributed more,

00:16:57.038 --> 00:16:59.620
but definitely you don't get a
completely fair return,

00:16:59.620 --> 00:17:02.759
because the whole idea is to
redistribute wealth and help the

00:17:02.759 --> 00:17:03.649
least well off.
 

00:17:03.649 --> 00:17:07.088
Okay, so that's one of the
cornerstones of Social Security.

00:17:07.088 --> 00:17:12.569
All right, going back,
now what happens to you after

00:17:12.569 --> 00:17:15.578
the first year you retire?
 

00:17:15.578 --> 00:17:17.861
After the first year you
retire, so when you're 65,

00:17:17.861 --> 00:17:19.914
you're getting 40 percent of
the average wage,

00:17:19.914 --> 00:17:22.380
if you're the average worker
throughout your life.

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:24.470
You know, it's 44 percent,
something like that.

00:17:24.470 --> 00:17:28.776
After that, your Social
Security benefit is indexed to

00:17:28.776 --> 00:17:32.838
inflation, so it grows at the
rate of inflation.

00:17:32.838 --> 00:17:34.928
The wage is probably growing
faster than the rate of

00:17:34.928 --> 00:17:35.420
inflation.
 

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:41.586
So as you get to be 75,80 and
85, your average benefit is down

00:17:41.586 --> 00:17:47.550
to 36 percent of the average
wage of the workers when you're

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:49.546
85,
but it starts off at 44

00:17:49.546 --> 00:17:52.230
percent, assuming you were
average your whole life.

00:17:52.230 --> 00:17:56.218
It'll be 44 percent and
gradually decline if wages grow

00:17:56.218 --> 00:17:57.769
faster than prices.
 

00:17:57.769 --> 00:18:02.207
So it's insuring you against
living long, because the benefit

00:18:02.207 --> 00:18:03.759
carries on forever.
 

00:18:03.759 --> 00:18:06.516
It's insuring you against
inflation, because it's

00:18:06.516 --> 00:18:07.778
inflation corrected.
 

00:18:07.778 --> 00:18:12.087
It's in a way insuring you
against feeling like a loser,

00:18:12.087 --> 00:18:16.943
because you're always going to
start off with a fraction of the

00:18:16.943 --> 00:18:18.588
new average wage.
 

00:18:18.588 --> 00:18:21.294
So if your children,
if the whole country grows

00:18:21.294 --> 00:18:24.528
incredibly fast and your
children are incredibly wealthy

00:18:24.528 --> 00:18:28.115
and getting high average wages
and every young person's making

00:18:28.115 --> 00:18:30.516
a lot,
the old won't feel totally left

00:18:30.516 --> 00:18:30.778
out.
 

00:18:30.778 --> 00:18:34.029
They'll be keeping up with
them, 40 percent of them anyway,

00:18:34.029 --> 00:18:36.618
and similarly,
if the young have a horrible

00:18:36.618 --> 00:18:39.210
time and aren't making very much
money,

00:18:39.210 --> 00:18:41.910
the benefits to the old also go
way down,

00:18:41.910 --> 00:18:44.700
because they're getting 44
percent of a much lower number.

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:49.083
So it's every generation in it
together and redistributing

00:18:49.083 --> 00:18:52.390
wealth from the richer to the
less rich,

00:18:52.390 --> 00:18:56.993
protecting you against long
life, making sure that you have

00:18:56.993 --> 00:19:00.250
some money no matter how long
you live.

00:19:00.250 --> 00:19:01.480
That's the idea of the system.
 

00:19:01.480 --> 00:19:06.761
So are there any questions
about how this mechanically

00:19:06.761 --> 00:19:07.559
works?
 

00:19:07.559 --> 00:19:17.328
Okay.
 

00:19:17.328 --> 00:19:19.617
Now it's very hard to do this
in the market,

00:19:19.617 --> 00:19:20.308
by the way.
 

00:19:20.308 --> 00:19:22.920
If you wanted to,
for example now,

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:26.636
think to yourself,
"Oh, I'd like to protect

00:19:26.636 --> 00:19:29.009
myself against my old age.
 

00:19:29.009 --> 00:19:32.016
I'm three years out of Yale and
I've fallen into an incredible

00:19:32.016 --> 00:19:33.890
job that's paying me a huge
fortune.

00:19:33.890 --> 00:19:37.368
I might want to retire early
and be a writer the rest of my

00:19:37.368 --> 00:19:38.150
life."
 

00:19:38.150 --> 00:19:43.595
You can't easily find an
annuity in the private market

00:19:43.595 --> 00:19:48.630
that's going to tell you that
when you hit 65,

00:19:48.630 --> 00:19:50.710
it will continue paying you for
the rest of your life.

00:19:50.710 --> 00:19:54.115
You can actually find them,
but they're incredibly bad

00:19:54.115 --> 00:19:54.630
deals.
 

00:19:54.630 --> 00:19:58.894
The reason that they're bad
deals is that the people who

00:19:58.894 --> 00:20:03.548
would have to take the money now
and give it back to you when

00:20:03.548 --> 00:20:06.000
you're old,
first of all you have to worry

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.340
whether they're going to be
around and still be able to pay

00:20:08.340 --> 00:20:09.308
you when you get old.
 

00:20:09.308 --> 00:20:12.096
And secondly,
they're worried that the only

00:20:12.096 --> 00:20:15.880
people who come to them are
people whose families live 100

00:20:15.880 --> 00:20:17.898
years,
and so they're going to have to

00:20:17.898 --> 00:20:20.269
pay a lot longer than they would
for the average person.

00:20:20.269 --> 00:20:22.540
So they're afraid of getting a
bad selection,

00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:25.586
that is, a selection of super
healthy people wanting to make

00:20:25.586 --> 00:20:26.308
that deal.
 

00:20:26.308 --> 00:20:29.305
And so they basically assume
that you're going to live to 100

00:20:29.305 --> 00:20:32.298
and so they're giving you a very
low annuity year by year.

00:20:32.298 --> 00:20:36.787
So Social Security is doing
something that's very hard to

00:20:36.787 --> 00:20:38.630
obtain in the market.
 

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:45.170
Now, so what went wrong?
 

00:20:45.170 --> 00:20:47.970
Oh, I should say a couple other
things about it,

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:49.519
some interesting things.
 

00:20:49.519 --> 00:20:52.019
You can choose to retire early
if you want.

00:20:52.019 --> 00:20:54.981
If you retire before 65 and you
want to get your payments

00:20:54.981 --> 00:20:56.965
starting earlier,
they say, "Okay,

00:20:56.965 --> 00:20:58.942
you can do that,
but we're going to cut the

00:20:58.942 --> 00:21:01.402
payments every year,"
and they make some actuarial

00:21:01.402 --> 00:21:04.635
calculation so that it's fair,
based on how long the average

00:21:04.635 --> 00:21:05.450
person lives.
 

00:21:05.450 --> 00:21:07.858
So if you start at 63,
you get 2 extra years,

00:21:07.858 --> 00:21:10.308
but they know if you live the
average amount of time,

00:21:10.308 --> 00:21:12.750
how much to cut it down,
so that on average,

00:21:12.750 --> 00:21:15.335
you'll get the same amount as
if you did the normal thing

00:21:15.335 --> 00:21:16.118
retiring at 65.
 

00:21:16.118 --> 00:21:18.680
They've actually raised this
age to 67.

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:23.660
Now another thing is the
spousal benefit.

00:21:23.660 --> 00:21:25.670
This is actually quite amusing,
I think.

00:21:25.670 --> 00:21:31.819
So I had a secretary 20 years
ago who got married three times.

00:21:31.819 --> 00:21:35.048
So she consulted me about this.
 

00:21:35.048 --> 00:21:37.729
If you're a spouse,
you know, traditionally,

00:21:37.729 --> 00:21:41.220
one of the spouses wouldn't
work, typically the woman.

00:21:41.220 --> 00:21:48.000
And so the wife has the right
to 50 percent of her husband's--

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.767
or the husband has the
right--one spouse has a right to

00:21:50.767 --> 00:21:53.328
50 percent of the benefits of
the other spouse,

00:21:53.328 --> 00:21:56.670
just by virtue of being married
or having been married.

00:21:56.670 --> 00:22:00.054
So the rule is that if you've
been married for more than 10

00:22:00.054 --> 00:22:01.763
years,
then you can either take your

00:22:01.763 --> 00:22:04.123
own Social Security benefits,
or if they're bigger,

00:22:04.123 --> 00:22:06.308
you can take 50 percent of your
spouse's.

00:22:06.308 --> 00:22:09.088
And if you've been married to
several different guys,

00:22:09.088 --> 00:22:13.068
say, and you're not married to
any of them anymore,

00:22:13.068 --> 00:22:16.208
you can pick the guy who had
the highest income and get 50

00:22:16.208 --> 00:22:17.088
percent of it.
 

00:22:17.088 --> 00:22:22.532
So she tracked down her first
husband she hadn't talked to in

00:22:22.532 --> 00:22:24.618
30 years, and anyway.
 

00:22:24.618 --> 00:22:30.568
So okay, and there are a bunch
of other rules.

00:22:30.568 --> 00:22:33.538
Anyway, that's not really the
heart of the matter.

00:22:33.538 --> 00:22:37.385
The heart of the matter
is--just to give you an idea of

00:22:37.385 --> 00:22:38.170
the size.
 

00:22:38.170 --> 00:22:39.788
This was in 2005.
 

00:22:39.788 --> 00:22:44.150
So 157 million workers are
paying into it.

00:22:44.150 --> 00:22:48.509
There are 48 million
beneficiaries.

00:22:48.509 --> 00:22:50.108
It's a gigantic program.
 

00:22:50.108 --> 00:22:54.489
So imagine the cost of keeping
track of just who's alive,

00:22:54.489 --> 00:22:55.348
you know.
 

00:22:55.348 --> 00:22:57.654
When somebody dies,
they're supposed to stop

00:22:57.654 --> 00:22:59.210
collecting Social Security.
 

00:22:59.210 --> 00:23:00.980
How do they know that the guy's
died?

00:23:00.980 --> 00:23:03.940
I mean, that by itself is not
an easy thing to keep track of.

00:23:03.940 --> 00:23:05.650
They have to send the checks to
everybody.

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:07.632
Somebody moves,
they have to figure out where

00:23:07.632 --> 00:23:09.390
to send the check to the new
address.

00:23:09.390 --> 00:23:12.313
They have to get the taxes,
they have to make sure people

00:23:12.313 --> 00:23:13.880
are paying the right amount.
 

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:19.380
It's a huge thing involving
basically the entire population,

00:23:19.380 --> 00:23:20.818
a couple hundred million people
almost,

00:23:20.818 --> 00:23:24.395
either getting taxes,
paying taxes or receiving

00:23:24.395 --> 00:23:26.598
benefits,
you know, over 200 million

00:23:26.598 --> 00:23:26.990
people.
 

00:23:26.990 --> 00:23:30.343
It's an incredible amount of
paperwork and moving stuff

00:23:30.343 --> 00:23:32.329
around and figuring stuff out.
 

00:23:32.329 --> 00:23:36.068
So how much does it cost?
 

00:23:36.068 --> 00:23:38.210
How much money do they waste
running the whole thing?

00:23:38.210 --> 00:23:42.140
Less than 1 percent of the
benefits.

00:23:42.140 --> 00:23:46.933
Okay, so it's one of the most
efficiently run programs,

00:23:46.933 --> 00:23:51.993
maybe the most efficiently run
program government has ever

00:23:51.993 --> 00:23:53.058
devised.
 

00:23:53.058 --> 00:23:55.769
So it isn't that the thing is
going broke,

00:23:55.769 --> 00:23:58.318
as you might believe listening
to George Bush,

00:23:58.318 --> 00:24:01.914
because somehow they're pissing
away the money and just losing

00:24:01.914 --> 00:24:02.210
it.
 

00:24:02.210 --> 00:24:04.019
That's not the reason.
 

00:24:04.019 --> 00:24:07.815
Something else is happening,
because they don't waste much

00:24:07.815 --> 00:24:09.680
money running the program.
 

00:24:09.680 --> 00:24:11.920
Okay, this gives you an idea
just of the size of it.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:15.050
So this is 2005,
so you have to add 20 percent

00:24:15.050 --> 00:24:17.068
or something or 15 percent.
 

00:24:17.068 --> 00:24:20.392
So the benefits,
the contributions,

00:24:20.392 --> 00:24:21.759
593 billion.
 

00:24:21.759 --> 00:24:25.190
Remember, there's a tax rule of
12.4 percent.

00:24:25.190 --> 00:24:27.696
Then you have to pay out the
benefits, which is some other

00:24:27.696 --> 00:24:29.720
rule, depending on what you
earned in the past,

00:24:29.720 --> 00:24:31.700
so there's no connection
between the two.

00:24:31.700 --> 00:24:34.295
And in fact,
the contributions are bigger

00:24:34.295 --> 00:24:37.538
than the benefits,
so the trust fund is growing.

00:24:37.538 --> 00:24:40.920
Now look at the administrative
expenses, tiny.

00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:42.868
And there are some,
the railroad,

00:24:42.868 --> 00:24:46.106
when the law was first passed,
railroads were in trouble,

00:24:46.106 --> 00:24:48.420
so in order to get some senator
to vote for it,

00:24:48.420 --> 00:24:50.038
they had to hand money over to
the railroad.

00:24:50.038 --> 00:24:51.749
So anything,
something's going on with the

00:24:51.749 --> 00:24:52.250
railroads.
 

00:24:52.250 --> 00:24:56.613
But the other benefit is the
trust fund makes returns,

00:24:56.613 --> 00:25:00.400
because it's a 2 trillion
dollar trust fund.

00:25:00.400 --> 00:25:02.666
It was a little smaller than
that 2005, so it's earning

00:25:02.666 --> 00:25:03.130
interest.
 

00:25:03.130 --> 00:25:04.990
That's part of the extra
returns.

00:25:04.990 --> 00:25:07.973
You see why the surplus is
quite big now,

00:25:07.973 --> 00:25:10.660
but it's headed to be quite
small.

00:25:10.660 --> 00:25:15.548
Okay, so now what is the
argument about?

00:25:15.548 --> 00:25:18.019
What is the crisis of Social
Security?

00:25:18.019 --> 00:25:20.940
What do the Democrats and the
Republicans say?

00:25:20.940 --> 00:25:22.828
Well, you've just heard what
the program is.

00:25:22.828 --> 00:25:25.714
How attractive do you think it
is, and do you really think it's

00:25:25.714 --> 00:25:26.740
such a good program?
 

00:25:26.740 --> 00:25:30.380
So the main thing is,
it's going broke.

00:25:30.380 --> 00:25:32.259
Okay, so now why is it going
broke?

00:25:32.259 --> 00:25:33.240
It's not broke now.
 

00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:35.170
It's making more money than
it's paying out.

00:25:35.170 --> 00:25:37.383
But in the future,
it's very obvious,

00:25:37.383 --> 00:25:39.720
you can just look at the
demography.

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:42.338
It's very obvious that it's
going to--

00:25:42.338 --> 00:25:46.073
the benefit formula is so big,
and there are going to be so

00:25:46.073 --> 00:25:50.000
many people retired that the
payments you make to the old,

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.113
when I'm retired,
are going to be way bigger than

00:25:52.113 --> 00:25:54.358
the payments that the young are
making in taxes,

00:25:54.358 --> 00:25:56.140
provided the rules stay the
same.

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:58.130
So that's the main problem.
 

00:25:58.130 --> 00:26:02.482
Somehow the system got out of
whack and we have to figure out

00:26:02.482 --> 00:26:04.660
how to put it back together.
 

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:07.700
Now it's no surprise in one
sense that there's an imbalance,

00:26:07.700 --> 00:26:10.740
because there's nothing about
the rules that balanced it.

00:26:10.740 --> 00:26:13.640
I mean, the taxes you
pay--we'll look at this in a

00:26:13.640 --> 00:26:16.538
second--that's just some
formula, 12.4 percent.

00:26:16.538 --> 00:26:20.038
What's that got to do with the
benefits you're paying?

00:26:20.038 --> 00:26:23.732
Well, the benefits are 40
percent, on average of what

00:26:23.732 --> 00:26:25.578
young people are making.
 

00:26:25.578 --> 00:26:27.990
So basically,
somehow the system must have

00:26:27.990 --> 00:26:31.461
assumed that there would be
three young people for every old

00:26:31.461 --> 00:26:32.108
person.
 

00:26:32.108 --> 00:26:35.193
So the young people paying 12
percent each,

00:26:35.193 --> 00:26:39.160
the old guy getting 40 percent,
you know, 3 times 12.4,

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:41.288
it's close to 40 percent.
 

00:26:41.288 --> 00:26:44.397
So if the ratio of young to
old, young workers to old

00:26:44.397 --> 00:26:48.045
retirees getting benefits is 3
to 1, then the systems going to

00:26:48.045 --> 00:26:49.598
sort of be in balance.
 

00:26:49.598 --> 00:26:52.338
But if that ratio is very
different from that,

00:26:52.338 --> 00:26:54.811
the system--for example,
two young people for every old

00:26:54.811 --> 00:26:56.663
person--
the system's going to be way

00:26:56.663 --> 00:26:57.460
out of balance.
 

00:26:57.460 --> 00:27:00.381
And the formula has nothing to
do with how many children people

00:27:00.381 --> 00:27:02.028
are having or anything like
that.

00:27:02.028 --> 00:27:06.769
So it's not so surprising it's
gotten out of balance.

00:27:06.769 --> 00:27:08.594
But we're going to see,
there's a much more fundamental

00:27:08.594 --> 00:27:09.710
reason why it's out of balance.
 

00:27:09.710 --> 00:27:12.645
Okay, so the first problem is,
it's not in balance,

00:27:12.645 --> 00:27:14.759
but there are many other
problems.

00:27:14.759 --> 00:27:17.108
So why do Democrats like it so
much?

00:27:17.108 --> 00:27:19.440
Democrats say,
"Oh, it's wonderful.

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:20.858
We're helping poor people.
 

00:27:20.858 --> 00:27:24.400
We're redistributing things on
the basis of lifetime earnings.

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:26.759
We're sharing risks between
generations.

00:27:26.759 --> 00:27:27.838
We're all in this
together."

00:27:27.838 --> 00:27:30.441
As I said, if the young people
have bad wages,

00:27:30.441 --> 00:27:32.348
then the old get less benefits.
 

00:27:32.348 --> 00:27:35.038
If the young are booming along,
making huge wages,

00:27:35.038 --> 00:27:39.279
then the old guys keep up with
them,

00:27:39.279 --> 00:27:42.180
so there's less--so it's not
only insurance,

00:27:42.180 --> 00:27:46.108
but it's less jealousy and less
disparity in the population.

00:27:46.108 --> 00:27:49.098
And then you're protected
against long life,

00:27:49.098 --> 00:27:52.308
you're protected against
inflation,

00:27:52.308 --> 00:27:55.058
and you can't blunder away your
money,

00:27:55.058 --> 00:27:57.383
because you have no choice
about where your investment

00:27:57.383 --> 00:27:57.690
goes.
 

00:27:57.690 --> 00:28:00.438
The government's taken care of
it, so if you're a bad investor,

00:28:00.438 --> 00:28:03.009
you can't suddenly find that
you've lost all your money.

00:28:03.009 --> 00:28:08.308
So now what do Republicans say?
 

00:28:08.308 --> 00:28:11.733
And surprisingly--well,
anyway, you'll be surprised

00:28:11.733 --> 00:28:14.200
where I come out on this,
I think.

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:18.307
So Republicans say,
"This stuff is much less

00:28:18.307 --> 00:28:21.558
good than it sounds at first
glance.

00:28:21.558 --> 00:28:23.920
For one thing,
there are no property rights.

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:26.759
I mean, who's to say what I'm
going to get when I'm old?

00:28:26.759 --> 00:28:29.230
Nobody even knows what they're
going to get when they're old.

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:31.088
I defy you,"
a Republican would say,

00:28:31.088 --> 00:28:33.430
"to tell me exactly what
your benefits are going to be,

00:28:33.430 --> 00:28:36.130
or even to explain to me how
they're calculated."

00:28:36.130 --> 00:28:38.490
"Virtually nobody in the
population can do that.

00:28:38.490 --> 00:28:41.673
That's just not right,
and you have no control over

00:28:41.673 --> 00:28:42.119
them.
 

00:28:42.119 --> 00:28:43.109
So what's going to happen?"
 

00:28:43.109 --> 00:28:44.058
a Republican would say.
 

00:28:44.058 --> 00:28:46.557
"One of these days,
the Democrats are going to say,

00:28:46.557 --> 00:28:47.740
'Oh, the system's broke.
 

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:50.075
We can't afford to pay
everything, so we're going to

00:28:50.075 --> 00:28:52.410
cut all the benefits in half' or
something."

00:28:52.410 --> 00:28:54.209
So a Republican would say,
"You know,

00:28:54.209 --> 00:28:55.568
they're not even my benefits.
 

00:28:55.568 --> 00:28:58.825
In order for me to really feel
good about participating in

00:28:58.825 --> 00:29:01.323
Social Security,
I want to know that when I put

00:29:01.323 --> 00:29:03.592
the money in,
what I'm getting out,

00:29:03.592 --> 00:29:05.230
and I want to own it.
 

00:29:05.230 --> 00:29:07.845
I don't want it to be some
vague promise that can be taken

00:29:07.845 --> 00:29:09.864
away from me,
and probably will be taken away

00:29:09.864 --> 00:29:10.690
from me."
 

00:29:10.690 --> 00:29:13.627
Okay, so it's a matter of
property rights and

00:29:13.627 --> 00:29:14.630
transparency.
 

00:29:14.630 --> 00:29:18.865
Then another thing is,
even if you did know this

00:29:18.865 --> 00:29:23.422
formula that I just explained,
people who want to retire and

00:29:23.422 --> 00:29:26.369
want to figure out how to plan
for their retirement,

00:29:26.369 --> 00:29:28.019
what does a normal person do?
 

00:29:28.019 --> 00:29:30.119
He says, "How much money
have I got in the bank?

00:29:30.119 --> 00:29:33.522
I've saved on my work;
I've got 100,000 dollars in the

00:29:33.522 --> 00:29:33.890
bank.
 

00:29:33.890 --> 00:29:36.902
Please tell me what the value
today is of my future Social

00:29:36.902 --> 00:29:37.960
Security benefits.
 

00:29:37.960 --> 00:29:43.078
If those are 8 million dollars,
then I know that my 100,000

00:29:43.078 --> 00:29:45.395
dollars,
I don't want to waste too much

00:29:45.395 --> 00:29:47.730
time trying to accumulate money
out of my savings,

00:29:47.730 --> 00:29:50.038
because I'll never catch up to
8 million dollars.

00:29:50.038 --> 00:29:52.707
If it's 50,000 dollars,
today's market value of my

00:29:52.707 --> 00:29:55.809
future Social Security benefits,
I know that I'd better be

00:29:55.809 --> 00:29:57.769
putting in a lot of money today.
 

00:29:57.769 --> 00:30:01.730
And I know how much money today
is, how big my savings are,

00:30:01.730 --> 00:30:05.622
relative to what the market
value is of my Social Security

00:30:05.622 --> 00:30:06.920
benefits."
 

00:30:06.920 --> 00:30:09.500
So the Republicans say people
just don't have any idea what

00:30:09.500 --> 00:30:12.453
the value of their benefits are,
even if they happen to know the

00:30:12.453 --> 00:30:15.843
formula I just explained,
nobody really can calculate

00:30:15.843 --> 00:30:16.808
what it is.
 

00:30:16.808 --> 00:30:20.404
Then thirdly,
the rich are giving money to

00:30:20.404 --> 00:30:21.368
the poor.
 

00:30:21.368 --> 00:30:23.240
Everybody knows Social Security
is doing that.

00:30:23.240 --> 00:30:27.519
Can you tell me,
what's the effective tax rate?

00:30:27.519 --> 00:30:29.308
Let's say I'm in the top tax
bracket.

00:30:29.308 --> 00:30:32.548
What is my effective tax rate
on Social Security?

00:30:32.548 --> 00:30:36.295
What fraction of my taxes are
being taken away from me because

00:30:36.295 --> 00:30:40.102
my benefits are going to be less
good, because I was one of the

00:30:40.102 --> 00:30:41.328
highest earners?
 

00:30:41.328 --> 00:30:44.538
There's virtually no one in the
country who's able to answer

00:30:44.538 --> 00:30:45.410
that question.
 

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:48.053
A Republican would say,
"What kind of a program is

00:30:48.053 --> 00:30:49.180
this if nobody knows?
 

00:30:49.180 --> 00:30:51.259
Okay," they'll say,
"we may sign on to the

00:30:51.259 --> 00:30:53.950
idea that the rich should give
some of their money to the poor,

00:30:53.950 --> 00:30:56.442
but at least tell us how much
of our money we're giving to the

00:30:56.442 --> 00:30:56.730
poor.
 

00:30:56.730 --> 00:30:58.630
We don't even know."
 

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:02.660
And then the Republicans say,
"We'd like equity-like

00:31:02.660 --> 00:31:03.380
returns.
 

00:31:03.380 --> 00:31:05.528
You know, why is it--"
This is what George Bush said.

00:31:05.528 --> 00:31:07.405
"Why is it that our
returns are going to be 2

00:31:07.405 --> 00:31:07.788
percent?
 

00:31:07.788 --> 00:31:12.250
I'd like to know that my money
is being invested in the stock

00:31:12.250 --> 00:31:17.009
market and earning what I could
get in the stock market."

00:31:17.009 --> 00:31:20.294
Anyway, Republicans,
savvy investors like to think

00:31:20.294 --> 00:31:24.249
that the money that they're
being forced to save can get the

00:31:24.249 --> 00:31:28.068
same rate of return as they
could get for themselves.

00:31:28.068 --> 00:31:30.183
Why should they be cheated in a
government--never mind that they

00:31:30.183 --> 00:31:31.460
have to give away part of the
money.

00:31:31.460 --> 00:31:33.569
The part that they're not
giving away at least ought to

00:31:33.569 --> 00:31:34.430
earn equity returns.
 

00:31:34.430 --> 00:31:38.640
And then Republicans tend to
think that choice is a good

00:31:38.640 --> 00:31:40.068
thing,
not a bad thing,

00:31:40.068 --> 00:31:42.288
and so if you let people decide
how to invest,

00:31:42.288 --> 00:31:47.318
it'll be better for them than
if you--

00:31:47.318 --> 00:31:49.640
even if some of the people make
mistakes.

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:52.363
Okay, so those are the
two--maybe some of you can add

00:31:52.363 --> 00:31:53.619
some other criticisms.
 

00:31:53.619 --> 00:31:55.250
Yeah?
 

00:31:55.250 --> 00:31:57.974
Student:
Wouldn't any system that

00:31:57.974 --> 00:32:01.259
insures against living longer
than expected,

00:32:01.259 --> 00:32:03.770
that annuity type system,
have that problem in terms of

00:32:03.770 --> 00:32:05.400
caring
&gt;?

00:32:05.400 --> 00:32:08.028
You'd be unable to calculate
the present value,

00:32:08.028 --> 00:32:11.630
precisely because you're unable
to predict how long you live.

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:16.683
So any system that successfully
&gt;

00:32:16.683 --> 00:32:21.740
is supposed to perform,
that's just an inherent issue.

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:22.278
Prof: Yes.
 

00:32:22.278 --> 00:32:27.430
So no, I don't think so,
because--so his question is,

00:32:27.430 --> 00:32:29.430
since we don't know how long
we're going to live,

00:32:29.430 --> 00:32:32.970
and the program continues to
insure you for your entire life

00:32:32.970 --> 00:32:35.130
and pay you for your entire
life,

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:38.910
how can you figure out what the
market value of that is?

00:32:38.910 --> 00:32:42.328
Well, the fact is,
there is no general market.

00:32:42.328 --> 00:32:45.284
So you're right,
there is no general market you

00:32:45.284 --> 00:32:48.230
can look at now today,
that will tell you,

00:32:48.230 --> 00:32:52.468
suppose we pay a fixed amount
of money for the average person

00:32:52.468 --> 00:32:55.094
in the economy,
what's the present value of

00:32:55.094 --> 00:32:55.380
that?
 

00:32:55.380 --> 00:32:58.961
However, that doesn't mean we
couldn't have a market like

00:32:58.961 --> 00:32:59.410
that.
 

00:32:59.410 --> 00:33:04.227
And so my solution is going to
involve precisely a market like

00:33:04.227 --> 00:33:04.778
that.
 

00:33:04.778 --> 00:33:09.480
So to answer his question,
it's not inherently impossible

00:33:09.480 --> 00:33:14.347
to attach a market price to
paying somebody for the rest of

00:33:14.347 --> 00:33:15.440
his life.
 

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:19.480
After all, you could imagine
Social Security now,

00:33:19.480 --> 00:33:22.538
paying, let's say 50 million
people,

00:33:22.538 --> 00:33:24.723
the people who are now retired,
each of them is going to be

00:33:24.723 --> 00:33:26.720
paid for the rest of his life
according to a rule,

00:33:26.720 --> 00:33:27.940
which we all understand.
 

00:33:27.940 --> 00:33:29.490
It just goes up with inflation.
 

00:33:29.490 --> 00:33:32.886
So you could say,
suppose you owned 1 percent of

00:33:32.886 --> 00:33:36.284
all those payments,
what would the value of that

00:33:36.284 --> 00:33:36.788
be?
 

00:33:36.788 --> 00:33:38.380
You could trade a security like
that.

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:40.615
Somebody could say,
"I want to buy today a

00:33:40.615 --> 00:33:43.675
security that gives me 1 percent
of all the payments everybody's

00:33:43.675 --> 00:33:46.105
going to get,"
or it could be 1 percent of all

00:33:46.105 --> 00:33:48.972
of the payments every 70 year
old today is going to get from

00:33:48.972 --> 00:33:50.140
Social Security.
 

00:33:50.140 --> 00:33:52.480
That's a well-defined thing and
it could trade in the market.

00:33:52.480 --> 00:33:53.880
You're going to see that the
market,

00:33:53.880 --> 00:33:55.118
as soon as we start talking
about this,

00:33:55.118 --> 00:33:58.470
there is an incredible number
of derivative instruments,

00:33:58.470 --> 00:34:00.180
they're called,
that trade in the market.

00:34:00.180 --> 00:34:02.674
That could be a new one,
and then there would be a

00:34:02.674 --> 00:34:03.440
market price.
 

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:07.063
You're going to see,
when I propose my plan,

00:34:07.063 --> 00:34:10.349
that it involves something like
that.

00:34:10.349 --> 00:34:13.097
Any other questions about the
rules of Social Security or

00:34:13.097 --> 00:34:16.139
whether you think they're bad or
good for some other reason?

00:34:16.139 --> 00:34:18.684
I've tried to list the ones
that struck me as the most

00:34:18.684 --> 00:34:19.260
important.
 

00:34:19.260 --> 00:34:19.989
Yeah?
 

00:34:19.989 --> 00:34:22.050
Student:
What does it mean by a return?

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:25.818
Does it mean that you invest in
government bonds and then you

00:34:25.818 --> 00:34:29.150
get back taxes from another part
of the government?

00:34:29.150 --> 00:34:30.199
Prof: Equity-like
returns?

00:34:30.199 --> 00:34:31.000
Is this what you're referring
to?

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:32.550
Student:
&gt;

00:34:32.550 --> 00:34:33.248
define the return.
 

00:34:33.248 --> 00:34:35.418
Isn't the interest you're
getting just taxes from another

00:34:35.418 --> 00:34:36.349
part of government?
 

00:34:36.349 --> 00:34:40.181
Prof: Okay,
so you can always do this

00:34:40.181 --> 00:34:42.963
calculation,
which has historically been

00:34:42.963 --> 00:34:46.119
done, and I'm going to show you
those numbers in a second.

00:34:46.119 --> 00:34:50.552
You can always look at how many
tax--let's take someone my

00:34:50.552 --> 00:34:51.719
father's age.
 

00:34:51.719 --> 00:34:53.389
My father actually died,
but a couple of years ago,

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:55.860
my father, he could look back
at his whole life,

00:34:55.860 --> 00:34:59.273
and he could look at how much
money he paid in Social Security

00:34:59.273 --> 00:35:00.730
taxes when he was young.
 

00:35:00.730 --> 00:35:04.119
Then he could look at what
benefits he got every year until

00:35:04.119 --> 00:35:04.880
that point.
 

00:35:04.880 --> 00:35:06.510
Let's say it was the day after
he died.

00:35:06.510 --> 00:35:08.730
I could look at what he got
every year until he died.

00:35:08.730 --> 00:35:12.920
So then I could just--that's
just a sequence of cash flows.

00:35:12.920 --> 00:35:15.945
We know how to calculate the
internal rate of return of that

00:35:15.945 --> 00:35:16.510
sequence.
 

00:35:16.510 --> 00:35:17.940
That's his rate of return.
 

00:35:17.940 --> 00:35:21.420
And I showed you in the graph a
long time ago that that was

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:23.159
actually done historically.
 

00:35:23.159 --> 00:35:24.070
We've done that.
 

00:35:24.070 --> 00:35:28.099
Leamer did that here.
 

00:35:28.099 --> 00:35:29.739
He did that for every
generation.

00:35:29.739 --> 00:35:31.518
Every birth cohort,
the average person,

00:35:31.518 --> 00:35:33.110
what their return was,
and you see,

00:35:33.110 --> 00:35:35.780
it was very high to begin with
and it become pitiful.

00:35:35.780 --> 00:35:40.467
If you forecast the future for
you, it's going to be less than

00:35:40.467 --> 00:35:41.389
2 percent.
 

00:35:41.389 --> 00:35:43.340
So Bush is saying,
"Why should you,

00:35:43.340 --> 00:35:45.940
young Yale undergraduate,
why should you be satisfied

00:35:45.940 --> 00:35:47.389
with less than 2 percent?
 

00:35:47.389 --> 00:35:49.768
Instead of paying those taxes
to Social Security,

00:35:49.768 --> 00:35:52.775
you put them in the stock
market, you get lots more than 2

00:35:52.775 --> 00:35:56.416
percent probably,
so why be satisfied with 2

00:35:56.416 --> 00:35:57.909
percent?"
 

00:35:57.909 --> 00:36:00.125
And Gore would say, "Well,
now we've got this pay as you

00:36:00.125 --> 00:36:01.621
go system,
you can't possibly put it in

00:36:01.621 --> 00:36:05.740
the stock market,
because then the old people

00:36:05.740 --> 00:36:09.510
aren't going to get it."
 

00:36:09.510 --> 00:36:12.809
Okay, any other questions?
 

00:36:12.809 --> 00:36:15.996
Any other reasons you think the
program is good or bad,

00:36:15.996 --> 00:36:17.059
Social Security.
 

00:36:17.059 --> 00:36:22.070
What's your feeling about
whether we should get rid of it

00:36:22.070 --> 00:36:25.469
or not or privatize it or change
it?

00:36:25.469 --> 00:36:27.239
Yeah.
 

00:36:27.239 --> 00:36:30.373
Student:
It discriminates against people

00:36:30.373 --> 00:36:32.760
who are predisposed to die
early.

00:36:32.760 --> 00:36:38.400
It favors couples whose ages
are really far apart.

00:36:38.400 --> 00:36:41.139
It's extremely
&gt;

00:36:41.139 --> 00:36:43.079
Prof: Yes.
 

00:36:43.079 --> 00:36:46.639
He's saying other problems with
Social Security is that it

00:36:46.639 --> 00:36:47.639
discriminates.
 

00:36:47.639 --> 00:36:50.909
It doesn't treat everybody
equally.

00:36:50.909 --> 00:36:53.650
His first example was,
people who you can reasonably

00:36:53.650 --> 00:36:56.766
expect to die sooner are going
to get a less good deal than

00:36:56.766 --> 00:36:59.559
people you can reasonably expect
to live longer.

00:36:59.559 --> 00:37:07.159
So what is the most basic class
that's being discriminated

00:37:07.159 --> 00:37:09.960
against, therefore?
 

00:37:09.960 --> 00:37:14.697
Who among you can you predict
are going to live less long than

00:37:14.697 --> 00:37:17.960
others among you,
at least historically?

00:37:17.960 --> 00:37:20.210
Presumably that will stay true.
 

00:37:20.210 --> 00:37:21.440
Student: Men.
 

00:37:21.440 --> 00:37:22.340
Prof: Men.
 

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:24.846
Okay, so men live 6 years less
long than women,

00:37:24.846 --> 00:37:26.590
so men are getting a bad deal.
 

00:37:26.590 --> 00:37:30.528
Now black men,
historically--although this is

00:37:30.528 --> 00:37:33.802
rapidly changing,
but black men lived even less

00:37:33.802 --> 00:37:35.983
long,
even worse by a considerable

00:37:35.983 --> 00:37:41.057
degree,
so you'd think it discriminated

00:37:41.057 --> 00:37:43.809
against black men.
 

00:37:43.809 --> 00:37:46.492
Black men also tended to be
poorer on average though,

00:37:46.492 --> 00:37:49.586
so they were getting a better
return per year than rich white

00:37:49.586 --> 00:37:50.000
men.
 

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:53.465
But anyway, a black man with
the same earnings got a much

00:37:53.465 --> 00:37:57.056
worse deal historically on
Social Security than a white man

00:37:57.056 --> 00:37:59.773
with the same earnings,
because on average,

00:37:59.773 --> 00:38:01.900
the black man died before the
white man.

00:38:01.900 --> 00:38:05.974
That probably had a lot to do
with healthcare and nutrition

00:38:05.974 --> 00:38:09.630
and stuff like that,
and this is rapidly changing.

00:38:09.630 --> 00:38:12.128
But anyway, certainly it seems
like men are going to get a

00:38:12.128 --> 00:38:13.179
worse deal than women.
 

00:38:13.179 --> 00:38:16.469
So yeah, there are all kinds of
little problems with Social

00:38:16.469 --> 00:38:17.659
Security like that.
 

00:38:17.659 --> 00:38:18.389
Anything else?
 

00:38:18.389 --> 00:38:23.650
He mentioned a couple of others
too.

00:38:23.650 --> 00:38:26.503
I regard those as less critical
though, than the problem of the

00:38:26.503 --> 00:38:28.576
thing going broke,
and these things which have

00:38:28.576 --> 00:38:29.590
split the country.
 

00:38:29.590 --> 00:38:32.396
It's been impossible--so
basically, everybody thinks this

00:38:32.396 --> 00:38:33.849
is a logical contradiction.
 

00:38:33.849 --> 00:38:35.878
You can't do what the
Republicans want,

00:38:35.878 --> 00:38:38.389
at the same time,
do what the Democrats want.

00:38:38.389 --> 00:38:43.130
So what should you do?
 

00:38:43.130 --> 00:38:44.699
Anything else anyone wants to
say?

00:38:44.699 --> 00:38:48.639
Someone else had their hand up
before.

00:38:48.639 --> 00:38:49.170
All right.
 

00:38:49.170 --> 00:38:52.849
So why did the system become
such a mess?

00:38:52.849 --> 00:38:53.989
How did it go broke?
 

00:38:53.989 --> 00:38:57.239
How should we have expected it
to go broke?

00:38:57.239 --> 00:39:04.719
Did it all happen because there
was the baby boom?

00:39:04.719 --> 00:39:08.099
All right, so I want to tell a
little parable.

00:39:08.099 --> 00:39:11.610
It has nothing to do with the
baby boom.

00:39:11.610 --> 00:39:15.447
Okay, so imagine that--and I'm
saying it in terms of fathers

00:39:15.447 --> 00:39:18.699
and sons, but I could say
mothers and daughters.

00:39:18.699 --> 00:39:21.940
So historically,
it was men working most of the

00:39:21.940 --> 00:39:24.969
time, but let's do mothers and
daughters.

00:39:24.969 --> 00:39:30.583
So suppose a mother is old now
and sick and she needs an

00:39:30.583 --> 00:39:36.706
incredibly expensive operation,
a million dollars to save her

00:39:36.706 --> 00:39:39.360
or to extend her life.
 

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:42.351
She doesn't have the money,
so she goes to her daughter and

00:39:42.351 --> 00:39:44.880
she says, "I need a million
dollars."

00:39:44.880 --> 00:39:46.480
And of course,
the daughter who loves her

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:48.840
wants to come up with the
million dollars to pay for her.

00:39:48.840 --> 00:39:51.679
But, you know,
that's a lot for her to pay.

00:39:51.679 --> 00:39:54.445
So she thinks to herself,
"My mother not only gave

00:39:54.445 --> 00:39:55.947
me life,
but let's face it,

00:39:55.947 --> 00:39:58.083
without her,
my daughter wouldn't have any

00:39:58.083 --> 00:40:00.740
life and her daughter wouldn't
have any life and her

00:40:00.740 --> 00:40:02.929
granddaughter wouldn't have any
life.

00:40:02.929 --> 00:40:05.730
My mother's responsible for not
just me, but for all these

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:06.860
generations after me.
 

00:40:06.860 --> 00:40:10.891
Why should I be the one to pay
the entire benefit of my

00:40:10.891 --> 00:40:12.460
mother's operation?
 

00:40:12.460 --> 00:40:13.929
So you know what I'm going to
do?

00:40:13.929 --> 00:40:17.260
I'll give her the million
dollars, but when I get old,

00:40:17.260 --> 00:40:19.219
I'm going to go to my daughter
and say,

00:40:19.219 --> 00:40:21.833
'Daughter of mine,
I sacrificed for your

00:40:21.833 --> 00:40:23.579
grandmother,
my mother.

00:40:23.579 --> 00:40:25.630
I put up a million dollars to
save her.

00:40:25.630 --> 00:40:27.139
I'm broke now.
 

00:40:27.139 --> 00:40:30.195
Maybe I don't need an
operation, but I'm basically

00:40:30.195 --> 00:40:34.250
totally broke because I spent so
much money rescuing my mother.

00:40:34.250 --> 00:40:37.664
Why don't you do the same for
me that I did for my mother and

00:40:37.664 --> 00:40:39.260
give me a million dollars?
 

00:40:39.260 --> 00:40:41.836
And by the way,
you could use the same argument

00:40:41.836 --> 00:40:44.190
with your daughter,
and so it's really not so bad,

00:40:44.190 --> 00:40:46.168
because you're going to get the
money back when you're

00:40:46.168 --> 00:40:48.635
old.'"
And so the granddaughter agrees

00:40:48.635 --> 00:40:51.648
and pays the daughter,
and then when she gets old,

00:40:51.648 --> 00:40:53.309
she does the same thing.
 

00:40:53.309 --> 00:40:56.829
It goes on for generation after
generation.

00:40:56.829 --> 00:40:58.849
Now let's say it went on
forever.

00:40:58.849 --> 00:41:00.619
How did this happen?
 

00:41:00.619 --> 00:41:06.460
Did nobody lose anything and we
paid for the operation to begin

00:41:06.460 --> 00:41:07.119
with?
 

00:41:07.119 --> 00:41:11.829
Is this some kind of Ponzi
scheme or something?

00:41:11.829 --> 00:41:13.889
Where did the million-dollar
operation get financed?

00:41:13.889 --> 00:41:17.820
How did that happen?
 

00:41:17.820 --> 00:41:22.360
Who paid for it?
 

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:24.550
Yes?
 

00:41:24.550 --> 00:41:26.025
Student:
Don't you pay the opportunity

00:41:26.025 --> 00:41:27.030
cost &gt;
 

00:41:27.030 --> 00:41:28.639
million dollars and
&gt;

00:41:28.639 --> 00:41:32.030
individual lifetime when the
money could have gone and made

00:41:32.030 --> 00:41:35.130
money itself rather than
spending on the operation?

00:41:35.130 --> 00:41:36.896
Prof: Well,
you got a million dollars back,

00:41:36.896 --> 00:41:37.980
remember, when you were old.
 

00:41:37.980 --> 00:41:38.728
Student:
&gt;

00:41:38.728 --> 00:41:39.365
nothing more than a million
dollars

00:41:39.365 --> 00:41:39.909
&gt;
 

00:41:39.909 --> 00:41:41.949
Prof: Okay, exactly.
 

00:41:41.949 --> 00:41:43.130
So that's the whole point.
 

00:41:43.130 --> 00:41:48.976
The point is that the
daughter--just to repeat what he

00:41:48.976 --> 00:41:49.750
said.
 

00:41:49.750 --> 00:41:52.869
The first daughter paid a
million dollars when she was

00:41:52.869 --> 00:41:53.340
young.
 

00:41:53.340 --> 00:41:55.054
Yes, she got the million
dollars back,

00:41:55.054 --> 00:41:57.510
but when she was old,
and that's a long time later.

00:41:57.510 --> 00:42:00.969
So for that whole time,
she made a 0 percent interest.

00:42:00.969 --> 00:42:04.355
Now maybe the interest rate
was, let's say,

00:42:04.355 --> 00:42:08.547
over that many years,
we're talking about 30 years or

00:42:08.547 --> 00:42:11.530
40 years, a large amount of
time.

00:42:11.530 --> 00:42:14.538
So the interest rate could
easily, over 40 years,

00:42:14.538 --> 00:42:17.610
you divide 40 into 72,
you know, it's like 1 and 3

00:42:17.610 --> 00:42:19.239
quarters or something.
 

00:42:19.239 --> 00:42:21.920
So if the real interest rate
was 1 and 3 quarters,

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:24.369
something like that,
you could easily imagine,

00:42:24.369 --> 00:42:28.429
that was the doubling rule,
that 100 dollars could have

00:42:28.429 --> 00:42:30.159
been turned into 200.
 

00:42:30.159 --> 00:42:33.800
So the first daughter who took
her 100 dollars could have had

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:35.619
200 by the time she was old.
 

00:42:35.619 --> 00:42:37.659
She only got 100 when she was
old.

00:42:37.659 --> 00:42:41.012
So in present value terms,
she gave up 100 when she was

00:42:41.012 --> 00:42:41.510
young.
 

00:42:41.510 --> 00:42:44.791
She got, in present value
terms, 50 dollars when she was

00:42:44.791 --> 00:42:45.150
old.
 

00:42:45.150 --> 00:42:47.190
So she gave away 50 dollars.
 

00:42:47.190 --> 00:42:51.579
She paid for half the operation.
 

00:42:51.579 --> 00:42:54.159
Now where did the rest of the
50 dollars come from?

00:42:54.159 --> 00:42:57.289
Well, the granddaughter gave
100 when she was young,

00:42:57.289 --> 00:43:00.480
got 100 when she was old,
so in present value terms,

00:43:00.480 --> 00:43:03.780
she also lost 50 dollars,
exactly the same amount as the

00:43:03.780 --> 00:43:04.800
first daughter.
 

00:43:04.800 --> 00:43:06.119
She gave up the same thing.
 

00:43:06.119 --> 00:43:07.889
Her contribution was just as
big.

00:43:07.889 --> 00:43:12.800
Of course, it came a lot later,
so in present value terms,

00:43:12.800 --> 00:43:15.291
at the time of the operation,
the granddaughter's

00:43:15.291 --> 00:43:17.159
contribution is discounted
twice,

00:43:17.159 --> 00:43:18.650
so it's 1 half of 1 half.
 

00:43:18.650 --> 00:43:22.943
So she only contributed in
present value terms 25 dollars

00:43:22.943 --> 00:43:24.400
to the operation.
 

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:26.458
And then the great
granddaughter,

00:43:26.458 --> 00:43:30.000
she herself looks at it as a 50
dollar contribution,

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.280
but from the point of view of
the original operation,

00:43:32.280 --> 00:43:35.820
it's discounted 3 times,
so by 8, so it's 12 and 1 half.

00:43:35.820 --> 00:43:38.755
So 50 25 12 and 1 half 6 and 1
quarter, blah,

00:43:38.755 --> 00:43:41.559
blah, blah, forever,
adds up to the 100.

00:43:41.559 --> 00:43:45.068
So basically,
this parable shows how a

00:43:45.068 --> 00:43:51.137
daughter could share the cost of
her mother's operation among all

00:43:51.137 --> 00:43:54.202
the descendants,
pay completely for the

00:43:54.202 --> 00:43:57.230
operation with each generation
making the same contribution,

00:43:57.230 --> 00:43:58.619
the same sacrifice.
 

00:43:58.619 --> 00:44:01.925
Of course, the generations who
make it earlier are helping the

00:44:01.925 --> 00:44:03.927
mother more,
but the point is,

00:44:03.927 --> 00:44:07.773
every generation has made
exactly the same sacrifice and

00:44:07.773 --> 00:44:11.900
that's how the original mother's
operation got paid for.

00:44:11.900 --> 00:44:14.559
Now what happens in generation
10,

00:44:14.559 --> 00:44:16.697
the great great great great
great great granddaughter is

00:44:16.697 --> 00:44:18.072
going to say,
"You know,

00:44:18.072 --> 00:44:20.280
I never even heard of this
original mother.

00:44:20.280 --> 00:44:23.110
I couldn't care less about her
operation.

00:44:23.110 --> 00:44:25.880
It wasn't a very good operation
anyway, because she died three

00:44:25.880 --> 00:44:28.380
years later, because medicine
was so bad at the time.

00:44:28.380 --> 00:44:32.355
So why should I be paying my
contribution to that original

00:44:32.355 --> 00:44:33.820
mother's operation?
 

00:44:33.820 --> 00:44:35.699
Yes, I know that she's
responsible for my life,

00:44:35.699 --> 00:44:37.333
but you know,
I don't know anything about

00:44:37.333 --> 00:44:37.659
her.
 

00:44:37.659 --> 00:44:39.070
I don't even know her name any
more.

00:44:39.070 --> 00:44:41.389
How come I have to keep paying
for it?

00:44:41.389 --> 00:44:43.409
So I just want to stop."
 

00:44:43.409 --> 00:44:47.733
Now why is it going to be
actually difficult for that

00:44:47.733 --> 00:44:49.480
generation to stop?
 

00:44:49.480 --> 00:44:51.237
"I just don't want to give
my money to that first

00:44:51.237 --> 00:44:51.670
generation.
 

00:44:51.670 --> 00:44:52.579
I couldn't care less.
 

00:44:52.579 --> 00:44:54.090
Let's stop right now."
 

00:44:54.090 --> 00:44:54.610
Yes?
 

00:44:54.610 --> 00:44:56.916
Student:
She's not giving the money to

00:44:56.916 --> 00:44:59.637
her great great grandmother;
she's giving it to her own

00:44:59.637 --> 00:44:59.989
mother.
 

00:44:59.989 --> 00:45:01.889
Prof: Her own mother,
exactly.

00:45:01.889 --> 00:45:05.737
So you can't stop just in the
middle because it's like the

00:45:05.737 --> 00:45:08.710
gift is being re-enacted every
generation.

00:45:08.710 --> 00:45:12.090
So the new generation that
stops, even if they understand

00:45:12.090 --> 00:45:15.592
where the whole thing began,
they're not going to screw the

00:45:15.592 --> 00:45:16.800
original mother.
 

00:45:16.800 --> 00:45:19.909
They're going to screw their
own mother, which they probably

00:45:19.909 --> 00:45:22.438
don't want to do,
so they're not going to want to

00:45:22.438 --> 00:45:23.440
stop the thing.
 

00:45:23.440 --> 00:45:26.309
So to say the parable very
shortly,

00:45:26.309 --> 00:45:29.690
the first generation that got
taxes--

00:45:29.690 --> 00:45:33.510
got benefits without
contributing anything,

00:45:33.510 --> 00:45:35.559
that was a huge amount of money
that they got.

00:45:35.559 --> 00:45:38.869
Every generation after that
lost money,

00:45:38.869 --> 00:45:42.320
but that was all a way to pay
the first generation,

00:45:42.320 --> 00:45:45.490
and you can't stop the cycle
without screwing your own

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:46.090
parents.
 

00:45:46.090 --> 00:45:50.349
So it's very difficult for the
thing to be stopped.

00:45:50.349 --> 00:45:56.469
Now you could make it a little
bit more realistic by saying

00:45:56.469 --> 00:46:01.215
every generation,
wages grow every generation,

00:46:01.215 --> 00:46:06.070
say between 1 and 2 percent in
real terms.

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:07.880
That's the historical rate of
growth.

00:46:07.880 --> 00:46:10.173
By the way, it hasn't been so
great lately,

00:46:10.173 --> 00:46:13.179
but anyway, historically,
say 1 to 2 percent real growth

00:46:13.179 --> 00:46:13.889
of wages.
 

00:46:13.889 --> 00:46:18.489
So on an annualized basis,
if you did the same thing with

00:46:18.489 --> 00:46:23.500
each generation paying 12
percent of their youthful wages,

00:46:23.500 --> 00:46:27.539
you would find that--now we're
coming closer to reality--

00:46:27.539 --> 00:46:31.666
that every generation was going
to get between 1 and 2 percent

00:46:31.666 --> 00:46:35.617
return on their contributions,
because the young would

00:46:35.617 --> 00:46:38.530
contribute 12 dollars out of 100
say,

00:46:38.530 --> 00:46:41.590
but their daughter,
that lady's daughter,

00:46:41.590 --> 00:46:44.041
30 years later,
the wages would have grown by 1

00:46:44.041 --> 00:46:46.440
to 2 percent every year for
those 30 years.

00:46:46.440 --> 00:46:49.483
So 12 percent of that bigger
number would go to that

00:46:49.483 --> 00:46:53.242
daughter, and so there would be
a rate of return between 1 and 2

00:46:53.242 --> 00:46:53.960
percent.
 

00:46:53.960 --> 00:46:56.157
And that's exactly what Bush
and everybody else is

00:46:56.157 --> 00:46:56.739
predicting.
 

00:46:56.739 --> 00:47:01.222
So now you understand where the
1 to 2 percent comes from that

00:47:01.222 --> 00:47:02.840
you're going to get.
 

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:05.813
If the population is stable,
the ratio of young to old,

00:47:05.813 --> 00:47:09.117
the rate of return on Social
Security is going to be equal to

00:47:09.117 --> 00:47:10.880
the rate of growth of wages.
 

00:47:10.880 --> 00:47:13.472
So it's not 0 as in the first
parable, because wages are

00:47:13.472 --> 00:47:14.369
actually growing.
 

00:47:14.369 --> 00:47:17.342
It's between 1 and 2 percent,
which is a bad return compared

00:47:17.342 --> 00:47:20.114
to the rate of interest,
and that's why every generation

00:47:20.114 --> 00:47:20.820
is losing.
 

00:47:20.820 --> 00:47:26.030
Okay, so let's do one more
thing.

00:47:26.030 --> 00:47:28.856
So the baby boom,
does the baby boom make things

00:47:28.856 --> 00:47:29.940
worse or better?
 

00:47:29.940 --> 00:47:31.460
How can you think about it?
 

00:47:31.460 --> 00:47:34.030
It's so simple minded to think
this way.

00:47:34.030 --> 00:47:36.208
It's amazing;
the public is so confused about

00:47:36.208 --> 00:47:36.489
this.
 

00:47:36.489 --> 00:47:39.440
Suppose you have a baby boom
generation.

00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:41.407
So you're going on with all
these mothers,

00:47:41.407 --> 00:47:44.239
we're back to the mother and
the daughter with 1 million.

00:47:44.239 --> 00:47:46.824
So let's say there's one
mother, one daughter,

00:47:46.824 --> 00:47:48.719
one person in every generation.
 

00:47:48.719 --> 00:47:52.202
All of a sudden,
there's a baby boom generation,

00:47:52.202 --> 00:47:55.538
but of course,
to be old, you have to be young

00:47:55.538 --> 00:47:56.280
first.
 

00:47:56.280 --> 00:48:00.690
So let's say in some generation
after a bunch of times,

00:48:00.690 --> 00:48:04.449
there are 2 daughters instead
of 1 daughter.

00:48:04.449 --> 00:48:13.288
Each of them is not going to
pay--if the tax rate stays the

00:48:13.288 --> 00:48:20.449
same and the young daughters now
each pay 1,

00:48:20.449 --> 00:48:23.900
the mother who's alive then
only needs 1 when she gets old.

00:48:23.900 --> 00:48:27.748
So 2 daughters now have 1 to
contribute, so half of their

00:48:27.748 --> 00:48:31.182
money goes to paying off the
mother when she's old,

00:48:31.182 --> 00:48:34.070
just like would have usually
happened.

00:48:34.070 --> 00:48:36.983
But the baby generation,
because it's young first,

00:48:36.983 --> 00:48:40.489
that means when I was young,
my generation was making a huge

00:48:40.489 --> 00:48:41.679
amount of money.
 

00:48:41.679 --> 00:48:42.409
We're doing it now.
 

00:48:42.409 --> 00:48:43.760
That's why there's a surplus.
 

00:48:43.760 --> 00:48:46.869
There's this gigantic surplus
being put in to Social Security,

00:48:46.869 --> 00:48:49.800
and so when my generation gets
old,

00:48:49.800 --> 00:48:52.530
the dollar that didn't have to
go to the mother,

00:48:52.530 --> 00:48:54.820
because there was an extra
dollar there,

00:48:54.820 --> 00:48:57.230
that could be earning the rate
of interest.

00:48:57.230 --> 00:48:59.510
And so at the end,
when we get old,

00:48:59.510 --> 00:49:02.753
there are going to be 2 of us,
and there's only going to be 1

00:49:02.753 --> 00:49:04.969
child next generation to
contribute 1,

00:49:04.969 --> 00:49:06.639
and we're going to be expecting
1.

00:49:06.639 --> 00:49:09.713
But see, the 1 that was put in
when we were young has now grown

00:49:09.713 --> 00:49:10.059
to 2.
 

00:49:10.059 --> 00:49:11.824
You've got 2 there,
plus another 1,

00:49:11.824 --> 00:49:14.264
that's 3, so there actually
should be a surplus,

00:49:14.264 --> 00:49:15.199
not a deficit.
 

