01:01:07.739 --> 01:01:10.996
So the generation that
benefited the most was my

01:01:10.996 --> 01:01:14.530
father's generation and James
Tobin's generation.

01:01:14.530 --> 01:01:17.130
Tobin, as we'll see in a
second, he used to tell me all

01:01:17.130 --> 01:01:18.811
the time--
he was Yale's most famous

01:01:18.811 --> 01:01:20.788
economist,
and I happen to be the James

01:01:20.788 --> 01:01:23.288
Tobin professor,
so I have quite a fondness for

01:01:23.288 --> 01:01:23.550
him.
 

01:01:23.550 --> 01:01:27.369
I also went to the same high
school he went to in Illinois.

01:01:27.369 --> 01:01:31.293
Anyway, he used to tell me that
the problem with Social Security

01:01:31.293 --> 01:01:32.963
was,
we didn't have enough--I didn't

01:01:32.963 --> 01:01:35.009
have enough children,
and I would tell him the

01:01:35.009 --> 01:01:37.219
problem with Social Security was
we gave him,

01:01:37.219 --> 01:01:38.807
his birth date,
too much money,

01:01:38.807 --> 01:01:40.980
and that's why we're all
suffering now.

01:01:40.980 --> 01:01:43.677
So you can see all the
generations and which ones,

01:01:43.677 --> 01:01:46.320
which generation got the most
amount of money.

01:01:46.320 --> 01:01:49.070
So that I also calculated.
 

01:01:49.070 --> 01:01:53.960
Now this parable is not exactly
accurate.

01:01:53.960 --> 01:01:56.029
So you know,
in the parable,

01:01:56.029 --> 01:02:00.320
we should have had a crisis in
1970, it should have been,

01:02:00.320 --> 01:02:01.239
or 1980.
 

01:02:01.239 --> 01:02:05.239
I told you the people in 1980
should already have realized--

01:02:05.239 --> 01:02:07.969
the generation starting to work
in 1980,

01:02:07.969 --> 01:02:10.929
so born in 1960,
a lot younger than you are,

01:02:10.929 --> 01:02:13.423
they should already have
realized that they're getting a

01:02:13.423 --> 01:02:16.195
bad deal in Social Security,
and so we should have had all

01:02:16.195 --> 01:02:17.280
this come much sooner.
 

01:02:17.280 --> 01:02:24.250
So what kept the problem from
manifesting itself until now?

01:02:24.250 --> 01:02:26.802
Well, what kept the problem
from manifesting itself until

01:02:26.802 --> 01:02:28.489
now is actually quite easy to
see,

01:02:28.489 --> 01:02:32.804
is there were a lot more young
people per old in the historical

01:02:32.804 --> 01:02:33.780
generations.
 

01:02:33.780 --> 01:02:37.594
Now we're leveling off and
everybody thinks we're going to

01:02:37.594 --> 01:02:39.869
be 2 young people for every old.
 

01:02:39.869 --> 01:02:42.835
The story I sort of told,
working from 40 to 60 and

01:02:42.835 --> 01:02:45.445
retired from 60 to 80 in a
stable population,

01:02:45.445 --> 01:02:48.530
that's coming close to what
we're converging to.

01:02:48.530 --> 01:02:51.204
So there are going to be 2
young for every old,

01:02:51.204 --> 01:02:53.239
where there used to be 3,4 and
5.

01:02:53.239 --> 01:02:56.059
Now how could there have been
so many young for all the old?

01:02:56.059 --> 01:02:59.438
Well, you know,
women at the beginning,

01:02:59.438 --> 01:03:02.639
in this period,
they were working.

01:03:02.639 --> 01:03:04.909
Women were surging into the
labor force.

01:03:04.909 --> 01:03:06.795
There were a huge number of
young women working,

01:03:06.795 --> 01:03:08.599
but their mothers actually
weren't working.

01:03:08.599 --> 01:03:11.648
They had not worked and so they
were getting half their

01:03:11.648 --> 01:03:14.646
husband's benefits,
not the full benefit that these

01:03:14.646 --> 01:03:18.219
daughters who were working their
whole lives are going to get.

01:03:18.219 --> 01:03:19.940
They're not going to take half
their husband's benefits.

01:03:19.940 --> 01:03:21.384
They're going to take all their
own benefits,

01:03:21.384 --> 01:03:22.599
which are going to be a lot
higher.

01:03:22.599 --> 01:03:27.329
So then there was the baby boom
generation.

01:03:27.329 --> 01:03:30.036
The baby boom generation,
far from causing the problem,

01:03:30.036 --> 01:03:31.389
has deferred the problem.
 

01:03:31.389 --> 01:03:35.585
There are all these surpluses,
because we were working so

01:03:35.585 --> 01:03:36.110
long.
 

01:03:36.110 --> 01:03:37.929
I don't want to get into all
the details.

01:03:37.929 --> 01:03:44.280
People are living longer now
too, so that's another problem.

01:03:44.280 --> 01:03:47.139
Too much complication here.
 

01:03:47.139 --> 01:03:49.139
Okay, so what can you do about
this?

01:03:49.139 --> 01:03:57.429
Well, there are obvious things
to do, which are bad.

01:03:57.429 --> 01:03:59.449
So one thing you could do is,
you could say,

01:03:59.449 --> 01:04:02.847
if we're supposed to be paying
the average young [correction:

01:04:02.847 --> 01:04:04.659
old]
person 40 percent of the new

01:04:04.659 --> 01:04:07.458
generation's wages,
and there are only going to be

01:04:07.458 --> 01:04:09.280
2 young people for every old
person,

01:04:09.280 --> 01:04:13.730
we could maybe shave the 40
percent down a little bit.

01:04:13.730 --> 01:04:16.527
Let's make the Social Security
tax 18 percent instead of 12

01:04:16.527 --> 01:04:17.010
percent.
 

01:04:17.010 --> 01:04:23.440
So you could raise it by 6
percent.

01:04:23.440 --> 01:04:27.722
Nobody wants to actually do
that, because an increase of 6

01:04:27.722 --> 01:04:31.929
percent in a tax rate is an
astronomical increase and you

01:04:31.929 --> 01:04:36.288
can read in the newspapers how
loath Congress is to raising

01:04:36.288 --> 01:04:37.190
taxes.
 

01:04:37.190 --> 01:04:41.914
Another obvious thing you could
do is, you could raise

01:04:41.914 --> 01:04:43.429
retirement age.
 

01:04:43.429 --> 01:04:47.307
So instead of saying it's 65,
because people will live till

01:04:47.307 --> 01:04:49.126
80,
make it start at 67,

01:04:49.126 --> 01:04:53.161
so you'll only have to pay them
for 13 years instead of 15

01:04:53.161 --> 01:04:53.800
years.
 

01:04:53.800 --> 01:04:56.969
In this example,
18 years instead of 20 years.

01:04:56.969 --> 01:04:59.579
So you could keep raising the
retirement age.

01:04:59.579 --> 01:05:02.101
The problem with that is--not
the retirement age,

01:05:02.101 --> 01:05:04.570
the age you start collecting
Social Security.

01:05:04.570 --> 01:05:08.166
The problem with that of course
is that people are retiring not

01:05:08.166 --> 01:05:10.614
later and later,
even younger and younger,

01:05:10.614 --> 01:05:13.050
believe it or not,
and so you're getting this huge

01:05:13.050 --> 01:05:15.554
gap between when people retire
and when they start getting

01:05:15.554 --> 01:05:16.389
Social Security.
 

01:05:16.389 --> 01:05:18.527
So there's a limit to
how--obviously you should do a

01:05:18.527 --> 01:05:20.625
little bit of that,
but there's a limit of how much

01:05:20.625 --> 01:05:21.590
of that you can do.
 

01:05:21.590 --> 01:05:25.219
So you need to make not just a
parametric reform,

01:05:25.219 --> 01:05:27.981
you know, like adjusting a
number, changing the tax rate a

01:05:27.981 --> 01:05:30.056
little bit,
but I believe you need a

01:05:30.056 --> 01:05:32.434
fundamental reform,
and the Republicans have

01:05:32.434 --> 01:05:33.110
proposed one.
 

01:05:33.110 --> 01:05:35.159
They've said,
"Let's privatize.

01:05:35.159 --> 01:05:37.309
Let's change the whole
system."

01:05:37.309 --> 01:05:46.150
Okay, so what does it mean to
privatize?

01:05:46.150 --> 01:05:47.860
How are they going to do that?
 

01:05:47.860 --> 01:05:53.054
So what Bush had in mind was
the following:

01:05:53.054 --> 01:05:57.880
he said, "What is
privatization?

01:05:57.880 --> 01:05:59.500
It involves three things.
 

01:05:59.500 --> 01:06:03.076
It's the creation of individual
accounts, so your name goes on

01:06:03.076 --> 01:06:03.369
it.
 

01:06:03.369 --> 01:06:05.849
So it's your account,
your money and no one can take

01:06:05.849 --> 01:06:06.530
it from you.
 

01:06:06.530 --> 01:06:09.501
It's your money and your
money's what's going to pay for

01:06:09.501 --> 01:06:11.610
your own benefits,
so it's prefunded.

01:06:11.610 --> 01:06:14.748
So it's individual accounts and
prefunded, and it's

01:06:14.748 --> 01:06:15.880
diversification.
 

01:06:15.880 --> 01:06:18.657
You're supposed to invest not
just in government bonds,

01:06:18.657 --> 01:06:21.539
but in the stock market,
whatever else you want."

01:06:21.539 --> 01:06:23.442
So those are the three
cornerstones,

01:06:23.442 --> 01:06:26.539
at least the way I've explained
them, of privatization.

01:06:26.539 --> 01:06:27.679
Three things that it
accomplishes.

01:06:27.679 --> 01:06:29.469
It gives you your name on the
money.

01:06:29.469 --> 01:06:30.699
It's your money.
 

01:06:30.699 --> 01:06:33.139
That's the money that's going
to pay you when you get old,

01:06:33.139 --> 01:06:36.679
prefunding, and you can invest
in a wider range of assets,

01:06:36.679 --> 01:06:38.884
especially the stock market,
which is what everybody seems

01:06:38.884 --> 01:06:41.155
to want to put their money in,
or at least used to,

01:06:41.155 --> 01:06:42.650
until we had this last crash.
 

01:06:42.650 --> 01:06:44.141
On the other hand,
the stock market's going up a

01:06:44.141 --> 01:06:45.760
lot, so people are getting less
nervous about it.

01:06:45.760 --> 01:06:51.989
So those things are different,
they're not the same.

01:06:51.989 --> 01:06:54.780
So how is Bush going to handle
this?

01:06:54.780 --> 01:06:56.929
How would you think he was
going to do this?

01:06:56.929 --> 01:07:01.369
How could you possibly--so Bush
said, "I want to privatize.

01:07:01.369 --> 01:07:05.059
I want the 12 percent that you
pay in Social Security taxes,

01:07:05.059 --> 01:07:08.260
I want 4 percent of that for
you to be able to put that in

01:07:08.260 --> 01:07:11.460
your private account in the
stock market with your name on

01:07:11.460 --> 01:07:12.190
it."
 

01:07:12.190 --> 01:07:15.010
So Gore said,
"Well, that's ridiculous.

01:07:15.010 --> 01:07:18.559
If it's only 8 percent then,
left to give to the old people,

01:07:18.559 --> 01:07:20.099
the old people are going to get
cheated,

01:07:20.099 --> 01:07:23.420
so how is Bush going to handle
that?"

01:07:23.420 --> 01:07:28.849
What did you think he was going
to do?

01:07:28.849 --> 01:07:29.969
Student:
Borrow the

01:07:29.969 --> 01:07:31.179
&gt;
 

01:07:31.179 --> 01:07:31.889
Prof: Could you say that
again?

01:07:31.889 --> 01:07:33.099
It sounds right,
but I couldn't--

01:07:33.099 --> 01:07:34.472
Student:
Borrow to make up the

01:07:34.472 --> 01:07:34.929
shortfall.
 

01:07:34.929 --> 01:07:36.469
Prof: Exactly.
 

01:07:36.469 --> 01:07:40.123
So I don't know what Gore was
thinking, especially since I was

01:07:40.123 --> 01:07:43.059
supposedly advising Gore about
Social Security.

01:07:43.059 --> 01:07:47.179
But he just said in the debate,
"That's impossible.

01:07:47.179 --> 01:07:48.599
You'll just screw all the old
people."

01:07:48.599 --> 01:07:51.980
Okay, so you're supposed to be
giving 12 percent,

01:07:51.980 --> 01:07:55.431
you know, 12 here,
-12 here, and then getting some

01:07:55.431 --> 01:07:56.909
return over here.
 

01:07:56.909 --> 01:07:59.525
And now Bush is saying,
"I only want to give you 8

01:07:59.525 --> 01:08:02.338
dollars,
and the other 4 you put in your

01:08:02.338 --> 01:08:05.478
Social Security account,
and then you're going to get

01:08:05.478 --> 01:08:06.969
maybe a much bigger return
here--

01:08:06.969 --> 01:08:09.030
sorry, in your stock market
account,

01:08:09.030 --> 01:08:12.360
in Social Security,
so you can't take it out."

01:08:12.360 --> 01:08:14.449
So Bush would say,
"Yes, let people put their

01:08:14.449 --> 01:08:16.921
names on it, force them to save
and contribute the whole 12

01:08:16.921 --> 01:08:17.689
dollars."
 

01:08:17.689 --> 01:08:19.805
Bush agrees that you've got to
force young people to save,

01:08:19.805 --> 01:08:21.550
because they're not going to do
it otherwise.

01:08:21.550 --> 01:08:23.908
So you put the 4 dollars in
their private account,

01:08:23.908 --> 01:08:26.599
but it's their name on it,
and then it grows to some huge

01:08:26.599 --> 01:08:28.896
number,
you know, 20 instead of just

01:08:28.896 --> 01:08:31.170
doubling by the time they get
old.

01:08:31.170 --> 01:08:33.810
And so that huge account is
their money.

01:08:33.810 --> 01:08:38.149
So that's what Bush would say.
 

01:08:38.149 --> 01:08:40.305
So Gore would say,
"If you take these 4

01:08:40.305 --> 01:08:44.460
dollars and give it to them,
how are you going to pay the

01:08:44.460 --> 01:08:48.359
old people who need the 12 right
up here?

01:08:48.359 --> 01:08:49.729
The old people are supposed to
get 12.

01:08:49.729 --> 01:08:51.890
How are you going to give them
their 12 when the young aren't

01:08:51.890 --> 01:08:52.970
handing over the 12 anymore?
 

01:08:52.970 --> 01:08:54.439
They're only handing over
8."

01:08:54.439 --> 01:08:57.506
Well, it's not like Bush and
his advisors didn't think about

01:08:57.506 --> 01:08:57.868
that.
 

01:08:57.868 --> 01:09:00.340
That would be a colossal
blunder.

01:09:00.340 --> 01:09:01.699
Of course they thought about
that.

01:09:01.699 --> 01:09:03.710
So what were they going to do?
 

01:09:03.710 --> 01:09:07.175
They were going to have the
government go out and borrow the

01:09:07.175 --> 01:09:10.640
other 4, so the government
contributes 4 that it borrows.

01:09:10.640 --> 01:09:13.216
And now of course over here,
the government's going to have

01:09:13.216 --> 01:09:15.420
to owe 8,
because it's got to pay back

01:09:15.420 --> 01:09:18.136
the 4 it owed in 30 years,
at we're assuming,

01:09:18.136 --> 01:09:20.289
100 percent interest over 30
years,

01:09:20.289 --> 01:09:21.399
has got to pay back the 8.
 

01:09:21.399 --> 01:09:22.078
You're all with me.
 

01:09:22.078 --> 01:09:26.550
So where are they going to get
the 8?

01:09:26.550 --> 01:09:30.020
Who are they going to get the 8
from?

01:09:30.020 --> 01:09:30.579
What?
 

01:09:30.579 --> 01:09:31.829
Student: Taxpayers.
 

01:09:31.829 --> 01:09:32.850
Prof: Which taxpayer?
 

01:09:32.850 --> 01:09:34.310
Student: All of them.
 

01:09:34.310 --> 01:09:36.060
Prof: Everybody.
 

01:09:36.060 --> 01:09:37.390
Really?
 

01:09:37.390 --> 01:09:38.792
Student:
The same people who are paying

01:09:38.792 --> 01:09:39.479
the Social Security.
 

01:09:39.479 --> 01:09:41.130
Prof: Okay, these people.
 

01:09:41.130 --> 01:09:45.211
So if you chose to take 4 of
your dollars out of Social

01:09:45.211 --> 01:09:49.520
Security and put it into your
Social Security stock market

01:09:49.520 --> 01:09:52.710
trust fund,
your personal trust fund,

01:09:52.710 --> 01:09:55.697
the deal is,
you have to pay the interest at

01:09:55.697 --> 01:09:56.970
the end of 30 years.
 

01:09:56.970 --> 01:10:01.109
So this 8 comes out of your 20.
 

01:10:01.109 --> 01:10:04.770
So these people pay back the 8.
 

01:10:04.770 --> 01:10:07.529
So basically,
to say it in a different way,

01:10:07.529 --> 01:10:10.729
the way you get to invest in
the stock market,

01:10:10.729 --> 01:10:13.319
according to the Bush
privatization rules,

01:10:13.319 --> 01:10:16.411
is these people effectively,
they're giving the 12 dollars

01:10:16.411 --> 01:10:19.082
anyway to the old,
but they get to borrow 4

01:10:19.082 --> 01:10:22.788
dollars and put it in their
private stock market account.

01:10:22.788 --> 01:10:25.279
And then they have to pay back
the amount they borrowed with

01:10:25.279 --> 01:10:26.250
interest, which is 8.
 

01:10:26.250 --> 01:10:30.194
But if the stock market does
better than the interest rate,

01:10:30.194 --> 01:10:32.779
then of course they make out
better.

01:10:32.779 --> 01:10:37.100
They get 20 - 8, which is 12.
 

01:10:37.100 --> 01:10:39.170
Okay, so is that clear how he
did it?

01:10:39.170 --> 01:10:41.328
So it's not a logical
impossibility.

01:10:41.328 --> 01:10:43.069
The problem with the Bush plan,
of course,

01:10:43.069 --> 01:10:46.828
is that if the money you put in
the stock market earns the same

01:10:46.828 --> 01:10:49.979
rate of return that you would
have gotten anyway,

01:10:49.979 --> 01:10:52.788
if the stock market earns the
same rate of return,

01:10:52.788 --> 01:10:55.420
100 percent over all those
years as the bond market,

01:10:55.420 --> 01:10:58.625
then this private stash you
have just goes back to paying

01:10:58.625 --> 01:11:02.115
off the government debt and you
haven't gained anything in the

01:11:02.115 --> 01:11:03.090
stock market.
 

01:11:03.090 --> 01:11:05.685
You get the same Social
Security benefits you would have

01:11:05.685 --> 01:11:06.300
had anyway.
 

01:11:06.300 --> 01:11:09.222
So these guys who opt into the
privatization program,

01:11:09.222 --> 01:11:10.908
let me repeat the Bush plan.
 

01:11:10.908 --> 01:11:13.529
If you opt into the
privatization program,

01:11:13.529 --> 01:11:16.917
you effectively do everything
you did before in Social

01:11:16.917 --> 01:11:17.750
Security.
 

01:11:17.750 --> 01:11:19.689
You pay your taxes that go to
the old people.

01:11:19.689 --> 01:11:21.988
You get the benefits just like
you did before,

01:11:21.988 --> 01:11:24.435
but on top of it,
you have the right to borrow 4

01:11:24.435 --> 01:11:27.259
dollars from the government,
invest it in stocks,

01:11:27.259 --> 01:11:29.966
and then at the end,
you have to pay back the

01:11:29.966 --> 01:11:32.488
government out of your stock
market return.

01:11:32.488 --> 01:11:35.234
So you're betting on whether
the stock market is going to do

01:11:35.234 --> 01:11:36.630
better than the bond market.
 

01:11:36.630 --> 01:11:39.010
That's effectively what the
plan was.

01:11:39.010 --> 01:11:43.380
Okay, so it's not a logical
impossibility like Gore said.

01:11:43.380 --> 01:11:45.420
On the other hand,
if you don't think the stock

01:11:45.420 --> 01:11:47.548
market's going to do better than
the bond market,

01:11:47.548 --> 01:11:49.189
you could end up being worse
off.

01:11:49.189 --> 01:11:51.363
You could put in 4 dollars
here, get only 6,

01:11:51.363 --> 01:11:53.689
and then you'd have to owe the
government 8.

01:11:53.689 --> 01:11:55.970
Where's the government going to
get the other 2 dollars from?

01:11:55.970 --> 01:11:58.149
It's going to reduce your
Social Security contributions

01:11:58.149 --> 01:11:59.359
[correction: benefits]
by 2.

01:11:59.359 --> 01:12:01.210
So that's the government plan.
 

